member.remarks:
A utility class that generates secure API keys for various scenarios including user-specific, temporary,
client-specific, and environment-specific keys.

Features:
- SHA256-based key generation
- Multiple key generation patterns
- Key validation capabilities
- Thread-safe operations

Example usage:


// Generate user-specific key
var userKey = ApiKeyGenerator.Generate(
    userId: "user123",
    appId: "app456",
    expiryDate: DateTime.Now.AddDays(30),
    salt: "custom-salt"
);

// Validate the key
bool isValid = ApiKeyGenerator.ValidateApiKey(
    apiKey: userKey,
    registeredKeys: new[] { "key1", "key2" }
);



> [!IMPORTANT]
> Always store and transmit API keys securely

> [!WARNING]
> Never expose the salt value in public code or configurations

> [!TIP]
> Use environment-specific salts for different deployment environments

Creates a unique API key by combining client credentials, permissions, and salt value.
The generated key is Base64 encoded and uses SHA256 hashing for security.

Example usage:


// Generate API key for a client with specific permissions
var clientKey = ApiKeyGenerator.GenerateForClient(
    clientId: "client_123",
    clientSecret: "secret_456",
    permissions: ["read", "write", "delete"],
    salt: "client-salt-value"
);
// Returns: "mK8pL4nR7qW2vY6tB3mD5fH8kN0sAxJ1jM8="

// Generate API key for a read-only client
var readOnlyKey = ApiKeyGenerator.GenerateForClient(
    clientId: "readonly_client",
    clientSecret: "readonly_secret",
    permissions: ["read"],
    salt: "readonly-salt"
);



> [!IMPORTANT]
> Store client credentials securely and never expose them in public repositories

> [!TIP]
> Use granular permissions to implement principle of least privilege

> [!NOTE]
> The generated key combines all parameters in the format: clientId-clientSecret-permissions-salt

> [!WARNING]
> Rotate client secrets periodically to maintain security

Creates a unique API key by combining environment name, service name, version, and salt value.
The generated key is Base64 encoded and uses SHA256 hashing for security.

Example usage:


// Generate API key for production environment
var prodKey = ApiKeyGenerator.GenerateForEnvironment(
    environment: "production",
    serviceName: "payment-service",
    version: "v1.0.0",
    salt: "prod-env-salt"
);
// Returns: "bK9pL5nR8qW3vY7tB4mD6fH9kN1sAxK2jM9="

// Generate API key for staging environment
var stagingKey = ApiKeyGenerator.GenerateForEnvironment(
    environment: "staging",
    serviceName: "auth-service",
    version: "v2.1.0",
    salt: "staging-env-salt"
);



> [!IMPORTANT]
> Use different salt values for different environments to maintain security isolation

> [!TIP]
> Include major version changes in the version parameter to manage API versioning

> [!NOTE]
> The generated key combines all parameters in the format: environment-serviceName-version-salt

Creates a time-limited API key by combining purpose, expiry timestamp, and salt value.
The generated key is Base64 encoded and uses SHA256 hashing for security.

Example usage:


// Generate 24-hour temporary key for file download
var tempKey = ApiKeyGenerator.GenerateTemporary(
    validity: TimeSpan.FromHours(24),
    purpose: "file-download",
    salt: "temp-key-salt"
);
// Returns: "xK2jM9pL5nR8qW3vY7tB4mD6fH9kN1sA="

// Generate 30-minute temporary key for password reset
var resetKey = ApiKeyGenerator.GenerateTemporary(
    validity: TimeSpan.FromMinutes(30),
    purpose: "password-reset",
    salt: "reset-salt-value"
);



> [!IMPORTANT]
> Temporary keys should be stored with their expiration time for validation

> [!TIP]
> Use descriptive purpose strings to easily identify key usage

> [!NOTE]
> The expiry timestamp is formatted as 'yyyyMMddHHmmss' in the key generation process

Performs a simple validation check to determine if the provided API key exists in the collection of
registered keys. This method is null-safe and handles empty collections gracefully.

Example usage:


// Example registered keys from configuration
var registeredKeys = new[] {
    "NFHUZqt0zmL6siZ7/ynQ8nljJtsQrT3h0+nQZHhIQhk=",
    "IDxvX6aT3XTERRpuHpMNtpcQVUo2rZ3Smtm83UPVfi8="
};

// Validate an API key
bool isValid = ApiKeyGenerator.ValidateApiKey(
    apiKey: "NFHUZqt0zmL6siZ7/ynQ8nljJtsQrT3h0+nQZHhIQhk=",
    registeredKeys: registeredKeys
);

// Handle validation result
if (isValid) {
    // Process authenticated request
}



> [!IMPORTANT]
> This method performs a simple existence check. For more detailed validation, use the overload with
> error message output

> [!NOTE]
> Returns false if registeredKeys is null or empty

> [!TIP]
> Use this method for quick validation in middleware or authentication handlers

Performs validation of the provided API key against a collection of registered keys and returns detailed
error information if validation fails.

Example usage:


var registeredKeys = new[] {
    "NFHUZqt0zmL6siZ7/ynQ8nljJtsQrT3h0+nQZHhIQhk=",
    "xK2jM9pL5nR8qW3vY7tB4mD6fH9kN1sA="
};

if (ApiKeyGenerator.ValidateApiKey(
    apiKey: "NFHUZqt0zmL6siZ7/ynQ8nljJtsQrT3h0+nQZHhIQhk=",
    registeredKeys: registeredKeys,
    errMessage: out string? error
))
{
    // API key is valid
}
else
{
    Console.WriteLine($"Validation failed: {error}");
}



> [!IMPORTANT]
> Always maintain a secure storage for registered API keys

> [!NOTE]
> The method returns false and sets appropriate error message for null or empty registered keys collection

> [!WARNING]
> Handle the error message securely to prevent information leakage

This class implements a simple caching system using a  for thread-safe operations.
Each cached item has an expiration time and is automatically removed by a cleanup timer.

Features:
- Thread-safe operations
- Automatic cleanup of expired items
- Configurable expiration times
- Type-safe retrieval
- Optional default values
- Expiration renewal on access

Example usage:

using var cache = new Caching(defaultExpirationMinutes: 30);

// Basic operations
cache.Set(key: "user-123", value: new User { Id = 123, Name = "John" });
var user = cache.Get<User>(key: "user-123");

// With default value
var config = cache.Get(
    key: "app-config",
    defaultValue: new Config { Theme = "dark" },
    saveIfNotFound: true
);

// Update with new expiration
cache.Update(
    key: "session-token",
    value: "abc123",
    expirationMinutes: 60
);

Uses collection expressions for simplified initialization.

Example:

_cache["key"] = new CacheItem
{
    Value = "cached value",
    ExpiresAt = DateTime.UtcNow.AddMinutes(30)
};

Runs every minute to clean up expired cache entries.
Example:
_cleanupTimer = new Timer( callback: _ => Cleanup(), state: null, dueTime: TimeSpan.FromMinutes(1), period: TimeSpan.FromMinutes(1) );

Used when no explicit expiration time is provided.

Example:

// Item will expire in _defaultExpirationMinutes
cache.Set(key: "session", value: sessionData);

// Item will expire in 60 minutes, overriding default
cache.Set(key: "session", value: sessionData, expirationMinutes: 60);

Used to prevent operations on disposed instances.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Once disposed, the cache instance cannot be reused.

Example:

if (_disposed)
    throw new ObjectDisposedException(nameof(Caching));

Creates a new caching instance with automatic cleanup of expired items.
The cleanup timer runs every minute to remove expired entries.

> [!NOTE]
> The cleanup timer starts immediately upon instantiation.

> [!TIP]
> Choose an appropriate default expiration time based on your application's needs and memory constraints.

Example:

// Create cache with default 30-minute expiration
var defaultCache = new Caching();

// Create cache with custom 60-minute expiration
var longCache = new Caching(defaultExpirationMinutes: 60);

// Create cache with short 5-minute expiration
var shortCache = new Caching(defaultExpirationMinutes: 5);

Performs the following cleanup operations:
- Disposes the cleanup timer
- Clears all cached items
- Marks the instance as disposed
- Suppresses finalization

> [!IMPORTANT]
> After disposal, any attempt to use the cache will throw an .

Example:

using (var cache = new Caching())
{
    // Use cache
} // Automatically disposed here

Provides a thread-safe way to check item existence with optional expiration renewal.

> [!NOTE]
> This method checks both existence and expiration status in a single atomic operation.

> [!TIP]
> Use expirationRenewal to extend the life of frequently checked items.

Example:

// Basic existence check
if (cache.Exists(key: "session-token"))
{
    // Item exists and is not expired
}

// Check without renewing expiration
var isValid = cache.Exists(
    key: "auth-token",
    expirationRenewal: false
);

// Check with custom renewal time
var exists = cache.Exists(
    key: "user-preferences",
    expirationRenewal: true,
    expirationMinutes: 120
);

Provides type-safe retrieval of cached items with optional expiration renewal.

> [!NOTE]
> Returns default(T) if the item is not found or has expired.

> [!TIP]
> Use expirationRenewal to keep frequently accessed items in cache longer.

Example:

// Basic retrieval
var user = cache.Get<UserProfile>(
    key: "user-123"
);

// With expiration renewal disabled
var token = cache.Get<string>(
    key: "auth-token",
    expirationRenewal: false
);

// With custom renewal time
var config = cache.Get<AppConfig>(
    key: "app-settings",
    expirationRenewal: true,
    expirationMinutes: 120
);

Provides a convenient way to handle cache misses with a default value.

> [!NOTE]
> Always returns the defaultValue type-safely when the key is not found.

> [!TIP]
> Use saveIfNotFound to automatically populate the cache with default values.

Example:

// Basic usage with default
var settings = cache.Get(
    key: "app-settings",
    defaultValue: new AppSettings { Theme = "light" }
);

// Save default if not found
var userPrefs = cache.Get(
    key: "user-preferences",
    defaultValue: new UserPreferences(),
    saveIfNotFound: true,
    expirationMinutes: 60
);

// Simple string with default
var apiKey = cache.Get(
    key: "api-key",
    defaultValue: "default-key",
    saveIfNotFound: false
);

Provides a convenient way to handle cache misses with a factory-generated default value.


> [!NOTE]
> Always returns the value from  type-safely when the key is not found.


> [!TIP]
> Use  to automatically populate the cache with generated values.




// Basic usage with factory
var settings = cache.Get(
    key: "app-settings",
    defaultValueFactory: () => new AppSettings { Theme = "light" }
);


// Save generated value if not found
var userPrefs = cache.Get(
    key: "user-preferences",
    defaultValueFactory: () => new UserPreferences(),
    saveIfNotFound: true,
    expirationMinutes: 60
);

Provides a thread-safe way to retrieve all valid cache entries with optional expiration renewal.

> [!NOTE]
> This method only returns items that have not expired at the time of retrieval.

> [!TIP]
> Use expirationRenewal to extend the life of frequently accessed items in bulk.

Example:

// Get all items without renewing expiration
var allItems = cache.GetAll(expirationRenewal: false);

// Get all items and extend their expiration by 2 hours
var items = cache.GetAll(
    expirationRenewal: true,
    expirationMinutes: 120
);

Provides a thread-safe way to implement the cache-aside pattern.

> [!NOTE]
> If the item exists but has expired, it will be replaced with the new value.

> [!TIP]
> This method is ideal for implementing lazy loading patterns.

Example:

// Basic usage
var result = cache.GetOrSet(
    key: "user-123",
    value: new User { Id = 123 }
);

// With custom expiration
var data = cache.GetOrSet(
    key: "api-response",
    value: apiResponse,
    expirationRenewal: true,
    expirationMinutes: 30
);

Provides a thread-safe way to implement the cache-aside pattern with lazy value creation.


> [!NOTE]
> If the item exists but has expired, it will be replaced with the new value from the factory.


> [!TIP]
> This method is ideal for implementing lazy loading patterns with expensive computations.




// Basic usage with factory
var result = cache.GetOrSet(
    key: "user-123",
    valueFactory: () => new User { Id = 123 }
);


// With custom expiration
var data = cache.GetOrSet(
    key: "api-response",
    valueFactory: () => apiResponse,
    expirationRenewal: true,
    expirationMinutes: 30
);

Provides thread-safe removal of cached items.

> [!NOTE]
> Returns false if the key doesn't exist in the cache.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> This operation is immediate and permanent. The item will need to be re-added if needed later.

Example:

// Basic removal
cache.Remove(key: "user-session");

// Handle removal result
if (!cache.Remove(key: "api-token"))
{
    // Handle key not found
}

// Remove and check in one operation
var wasRemoved = cache.Remove(key: "temp-data");

example.code:
await cache.RemoveAsync(
    key: "user-session",
    callback: () => Console.WriteLine("Remove complete"),
    cancellationToken: CancellationToken.None
);

member.remarks:
This method provides thread-safe caching operations with flexible expiration handling.

> [!NOTE]
> If expirationRenewal is true and the key exists, the value and expiration time will be updated.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The expiration time is always calculated from the current UTC time.

Example:

// Basic usage
cache.Set(
    key: "user-profile",
    value: new UserProfile { Id = 1, Name = "John" }
);

// With custom expiration
cache.Set(
    key: "session-token",
    value: "abc123",
    expirationMinutes: 60,
    expirationRenewal: false
);

// Update existing item
cache.Set(
    key: "api-key",
    value: "xyz789",
    expirationRenewal: true
);

example.code:
await cache.SetAsync(
    key: "user-profile",
    value: new UserProfile { Id = 1, Name = "John" },
    callback: () => Console.WriteLine("Set complete"),
    cancellationToken: CancellationToken.None
);

member.remarks:
Updates only existing cache entries. If the key doesn't exist, the operation fails.

> [!NOTE]
> This method is thread-safe and uses atomic operations for updates.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Unlike Set(), this method will not create a new entry if the key doesn't exist.

Example:

// Basic update
cache.Update(
    key: "user-profile",
    value: new UserProfile { Id = 1, Name: "Updated Name" }
);

// Update with new expiration
cache.Update(
    key: "session-token",
    value: "new-token-value",
    expirationMinutes: 120
);

// Handle failed update
if (!cache.Update(key: "non-existent-key", value: "new-value"))
{
    // Handle key not found
}

example.code:
await cache.UpdateAsync(
    key: "user-profile",
    value: new UserProfile { Id = 1, Name = "Updated Name" },
    callback: () => Console.WriteLine("Update complete"),
    cancellationToken: CancellationToken.None
);

member.remarks:
Provides thread-safe upsert operation for cache items.

> [!NOTE]
> This method will always succeed and return true, regardless of whether it performs an add or update operation.

> [!TIP]
> Use this method when you don't need to distinguish between add and update operations.

Example:

// Basic upsert
cache.Upsert(
    key: "user-preferences",
    value: userPrefs
);

// Upsert with custom expiration
cache.Upsert(
    key: "session-token",
    value: token,
    expirationMinutes: 30
);

example.code:
await cache.UpsertAsync(
    key: "user-preferences",
    value: userPrefs,
    callback: () => Console.WriteLine("Upsert complete"),
    cancellationToken: CancellationToken.None
);

member.remarks:
Performs periodic cleanup of expired cache entries in a thread-safe manner.

> [!NOTE]
> This method is automatically called by an internal timer at regular intervals.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The cleanup operation is atomic for each individual item but not for the entire cache.

Example:

// Internal usage by timer
private readonly Timer _cleanupTimer = new Timer(
    callback: _ => Cleanup(),
    state: null,
    dueTime: TimeSpan.FromMinutes(1),
    period: TimeSpan.FromMinutes(1)
);

// Manual cleanup if needed
private void ForceCleanup()
{
    Cleanup();
}

This method is called before any operation to ensure the cache is still valid.

Example:

public void SomeOperation()
{
    ThrowIfDisposed();
    // Continue with operation
}

Internal class used to store cached items along with their metadata.

Example:

var item = new CacheItem
{
    Value = "some data",
    ExpiresAt = DateTime.UtcNow.AddMinutes(30)
};

Stored in UTC format to avoid timezone issues.

Example:

item.ExpiresAt = DateTime.UtcNow.AddMinutes(30);

Can store any type of object, including null values.

Example:

item.Value = new User { Id = 1, Name = "John" };

This utility class implements a singleton pattern to maintain a single HttpClient instance
for efficient connection reuse. It supports all common HTTP methods and provides
serialization/deserialization of request and response data.

Features:
- Connection pooling through static HttpClient
- Support for all common HTTP methods (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE)
- Automatic serialization/deserialization of JSON data
- Configurable timeouts and headers
- Proper error handling with detailed exceptions
- Resource-efficient implementation

Example usage:

// Basic GET request
var client = HttpClientUtility.Instance;
var response = await client.GetAsync<UserModel>("https://api.example.com/users/1");

// POST request with data
var newUser = new UserModel { Name = "John Doe", Email = "john@example.com" };
var createdUser = await client.PostAsync<UserModel, UserModel>(
    "https://api.example.com/users",
    newUser
);


> [!NOTE]
> This implementation follows best practices for HttpClient usage by maintaining
> a single instance to avoid socket exhaustion.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Default timeout is 100 seconds but can be configured per request.

This public constructor allows injection of a  instance.
It initializes the HttpClient with default settings.


var instance = new HttpClientUtility(systemLogging: loggingInstance);

This method calls Dispose(disposing: true) to free managed resources
and suppresses finalization.


HttpClientUtility client = new HttpClientUtility();
client.Dispose();

Example:

await LogRequestDetails(
    request: httpRequest,
    headers: customHeaders,
    timeoutSeconds: 30
);

Sends a DELETE request to the specified URI and deserializes the response.

Example usage:

// Delete a user and get deletion status
var result = await HttpClientUtility.Instance.DeleteAsync<DeleteResult>(
    "https://api.example.com/users/123"
);

Sends a DELETE request to the specified URI and returns the raw HTTP response.
Useful when you don't need to deserialize the response or when you want to handle the response manually.

Example usage:

// Delete a resource without expecting a specific response type
var response = await HttpClientUtility.Instance.DeleteAsync(
    "https://api.example.com/resources/123"
);

if (response.IsSuccessStatusCode)
{
    // Resource deleted successfully
}

This method sends a GET request and automatically deserializes the JSON response to the specified type.
It supports connection pooling, timeout configuration, and custom headers.

> [!NOTE]
> The method will return null if the response content is empty or null.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Always dispose of the returned object if it implements IDisposable.

Example usage:

// Basic GET request
var user = await HttpClientUtility.Instance.GetAsync<UserModel>(
    uri: "https://api.example.com/users/123"
);

// GET request with headers and timeout
var users = await HttpClientUtility.Instance.GetAsync<List<UserModel>>(
    uri: "https://api.example.com/users",
    headers: new Dictionary<string, string>
    {
        { "Authorization", "Bearer token123" },
        { "Custom-Header", "Value" }
    },
    timeoutSeconds: 30
);

Sends a POST request with the specified content to the URI and deserializes the response.

Example usage:

// Create a new user
var newUser = new UserModel { Name = "John Doe", Email = "john@example.com" };
var createdUser = await HttpClientUtility.Instance.PostAsync<UserModel, UserModel>(
    "https://api.example.com/users",
    newUser
);

Sends a POST request with the specified content to the URI and returns the raw HTTP response.
Useful when you don't need to deserialize the response or when you want to handle the response manually.

Example usage:

// Send a notification without expecting a specific response type
var notification = new NotificationModel { UserId = 123, Message = "Hello!" };
var response = await HttpClientUtility.Instance.PostAsync(
    "https://api.example.com/notifications",
    notification
);

if (response.IsSuccessStatusCode)
{
    // Handle success
}

Sends a PUT request with the specified content to the URI and deserializes the response.

Example usage:

// Update a user
var updatedUser = new UserModel { Id = 123, Name = "John Updated", Email = "john@example.com" };
var result = await HttpClientUtility.Instance.PutAsync<UserModel, UserModel>(
    "https://api.example.com/users/123",
    updatedUser
);

This class extends the functionality of the HttpClientUtility class with methods
specifically designed to work with the APIResponseData type used in the application.
It provides convenient methods for handling API responses in a standardized way.

Features:
- Methods for handling APIResponseData responses
- Simplified error handling for API responses
- Support for JObject and dynamic data types

Example usage:

// Get data from an API that returns APIResponseData
var client = HttpClientUtility.Instance;
var userData = await client.GetApiResponseDataAsync<UserModel>("https://api.example.com/users/1");

// Check if the API call was successful
if (userData.IsSuccess)
{
    // Use the data
    var user = userData.Data;
}


> [!NOTE]
> These extension methods are designed to work with APIs that return data in the
> APIResponseData format used by this application.

Sends a DELETE request to the specified URI and deserializes the response to APIResponseData.

Example usage:

// Delete a user
var response = await HttpClientUtility.Instance.DeleteApiResponseDataAsync<DeleteResult>(
    "https://api.example.com/users/123"
);

if (response.IsSuccess)
{
    Console.WriteLine("User deleted successfully");
}

Sends a GET request to the specified URI and deserializes the response to APIResponseData.

Example usage:

// Get user data from an API that returns APIResponseData
var response = await HttpClientUtility.Instance.GetApiResponseDataAsync<UserModel>(
    "https://api.example.com/users/123"
);

if (response.IsSuccess)
{
    var user = response.Data;
    Console.WriteLine($"User name: {user.Name}");
}
else
{
    Console.WriteLine($"Error: {response.Message}");
}

Sends a GET request to the specified URI and deserializes the response to a JObject.
Useful when the response structure is not known in advance or is dynamic.

Example usage:

// Get dynamic data as JObject
var data = await HttpClientUtility.Instance.GetJObjectAsync(
    "https://api.example.com/dynamic-data"
);

// Access properties dynamically
var name = data["name"]?.ToString();
var age = data["age"]?.Value<int>();

Sends a POST request with the specified content to the URI and deserializes the response to APIResponseData.

Example usage:

// Create a new user
var newUser = new UserModel { Name = "John Doe", Email = "john@example.com" };
var response = await HttpClientUtility.Instance.PostApiResponseDataAsync<UserModel, UserModel>(
    "https://api.example.com/users",
    newUser
);

if (response.IsSuccess)
{
    var createdUser = response.Data;
    Console.WriteLine($"Created user with ID: {createdUser.Id}");
}

Sends a POST request with the specified content to the URI and deserializes the response to a JObject.
Useful when the response structure is not known in advance or is dynamic.

Example usage:

// Post data and get dynamic response as JObject
var request = new { name = "John", age = 30 };
var response = await HttpClientUtility.Instance.PostJObjectAsync(
    "https://api.example.com/process-data",
    request
);

// Access properties dynamically
var status = response["status"]?.ToString();
var resultId = response["result"]?["id"]?.Value<int>();

Sends a PUT request with the specified content to the URI and deserializes the response to APIResponseData.

Example usage:

// Update a user
var updatedUser = new UserModel { Id = 123, Name = "John Updated", Email = "john@example.com" };
var response = await HttpClientUtility.Instance.PutApiResponseDataAsync<UserModel, UserModel>(
    "https://api.example.com/users/123",
    updatedUser
);

if (response.IsSuccess)
{
    var result = response.Data;
    Console.WriteLine($"Updated user: {result.Name}");
}

This class contains extension methods for the IServiceCollection interface to register the HttpClientUtility as a service in the dependency injection container.
Example usage:
// In Program.cs or Startup.cs services.AddHttpClientUtility();
> [!NOTE] > The HttpClientUtility is registered as a singleton service.

Registers the HttpClientUtility as a singleton service in the dependency injection container.
This allows the HttpClientUtility to be injected into other services.

Example usage:

// In Program.cs or Startup.cs
services.AddHttpClientUtility();

// In a controller or service
public class MyService
{
    private readonly HttpClientUtility _httpClient;

    public MyService(HttpClientUtility httpClient)
    {
        _httpClient = httpClient;
    }

    public async Task<UserModel> GetUserAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _httpClient.GetAsync<UserModel>($"https://api.example.com/users/{id}");
    }
}

This method calls Dispose(disposing: true) to release managed resources
and suppresses finalization to avoid redundant resource cleanup.


using (var db = new CouchBaseHelper())
{
    // Use db
} // Automatically disposed here

This method calls Dispose(disposing: true) to free managed resources
and suppresses finalization.


using (var db = new CouchBaseHelper())
{
    // Use db
} // Automatically disposed here

This method calls Dispose(disposing: true) to free managed resources
and suppresses finalization.


await using var db = new CouchBaseHelper();
// Use db

This property reflects the current connection status to the CouchBase server.


var helper = new CouchBaseHelper();
bool status = helper.IsConnected;

example.code:
// Basic Usage
using var db = new PostgreHelper(connectionString: "Host=localhost;Database=mydb;Username=user;Password=pass");
db.Connect()
  .ExecuteQuery(
    query: "SELECT * FROM Users",
    result: out List<JObject> users)
  .Disconnect();

// Transaction Usage
using var db = new PostgreHelper(connectionString: "Host=localhost;Database=mydb;Username=user;Password=pass");
db.Connect()
  .TransactionBegin()
  .ExecuteNonQuery(
    query: "INSERT INTO Users (Name) VALUES (@name)",
    parameters: new { name = "John" },
    rowsAffected: out int rows)
  .TransactionCommit()
  .Disconnect();

member.remarks:
Switches the current database context to the specified database name. If the target database is already the active one, no change will occur.
Features: - Database context switching - Connection state preservation - Method chaining support - Validation checks
Example Request:
{ "database": "target_database_name" }
Example Usage:
var db = new PostgreHelper("connection_string");
// Basic usage db.Connect() .ChangeDB(database: "new_database") .ExecuteNonQuery( sql: "INSERT INTO Users (Name) VALUES (@name)", parameters: new { name = "John" }, out _ );
// With transaction db.Connect(useTransaction: true) .ChangeDB(database: "new_database") .ExecuteNonQuery( sql: "INSERT INTO Users (Name) VALUES (@name)", parameters: new { name = "John" }, out _ ) .TransactionCommit();
> [!IMPORTANT] > Database must exist and user must have access permissions
> [!NOTE] > Active queries will continue on previous database
> [!TIP] > Use transactions when changing databases during critical operations
> [!CAUTION] > Ensure all operations on previous database are complete
> [!WARNING] > Connection string must have necessary permissions

Performs asynchronous database switching operation with optional callback execution.
Maintains connection state and handles errors appropriately.

Features:
- Asynchronous database switching
- Connection state preservation
- Optional callback execution
- Cancellation support
- Error handling and logging

Example Request:


{
  "database": "target_database_name",
  "callback": "optional_action_after_switch",
  "cancellationToken": "optional_cancellation_token"
}



Example Usage:


// Basic database switch
await db.ChangeDBAsync(
    database: "new_database"
);

// Advanced usage with callback and cancellation
var cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
await db.ChangeDBAsync(
    database: "new_database",
    callback: helper => Console.WriteLine($"Switched to {helper._connection.Database}"),
    cancellationToken: cts.Token
);

// Chain operations
await db.ChangeDBAsync(database: "analytics_db")
    .ContinueWith(async task => {
        var helper = await task;
        await helper.ExecuteQueryAsync("SELECT * FROM metrics");
    });



> [!IMPORTANT]
> Database must exist and user must have access permissions

> [!NOTE]
> No-op if target database is current database

> [!TIP]
> Use callback to verify database switch

> [!CAUTION]
> Active queries will be terminated

> [!WARNING]
> Active transactions will be rolled back

Opens database connection if not already open and optionally starts new transaction.

Features:
- Connection pooling
- Optional transaction management
- Method chaining support
- Error logging
- Connection state validation

Example Request:


{
  "useTransaction": true
}



Example Usage:


var db = new PostgreHelper("connection_string");

// Basic connection
db.Connect()
  .ExecuteNonQuery(
    sql: "INSERT INTO Users (Name) VALUES (@name)",
    parameters: new { name = "John" },
    out _
  );

// With transaction
try
{
    db.Connect(useTransaction: true)
      .ExecuteNonQuery(
        sql: "INSERT INTO Users (Name) VALUES (@name)",
        parameters: new { name = "John" },
        out _
      )
      .TransactionCommit();
}
catch
{
    db.TransactionRollback();
    throw;
}



> [!IMPORTANT]
> Ensure proper connection string configuration before calling this method

> [!NOTE]
> If connection is already open, this method will reuse the existing connection

> [!TIP]
> Use transactions for operations that need to be atomic

> [!CAUTION]
> Verify connection string parameters before connecting

> [!WARNING]
> Connection timeout may occur in poor network conditions

Opens database connection asynchronously if not already open.
Optionally starts new transaction.
Executes callback if provided after successful connection.

Features:
- Asynchronous connection
- Connection pooling
- Optional transaction management
- Callback execution support
- Cancellation handling
- Error logging

Example Request:


{
  "useTransaction": true,
  "callback": "optional_action_after_connect",
  "cancellationToken": "optional_cancellation_token"
}



Example Usage:


// Basic connection
await db.ConnectAsync();

// With transaction
await db.ConnectAsync(
    useTransaction: true
);

// Advanced usage with callback and cancellation
var cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
await db.ConnectAsync(
    useTransaction: true,
    callback: helper => Console.WriteLine($"Connected to {helper._connection.Database}"),
    cancellationToken: cts.Token
);

// Chain operations
await db.ConnectAsync()
    .ContinueWith(async task => {
        var helper = await task;
        await helper.ExecuteQueryAsync("SELECT version()");
    });



> [!IMPORTANT]
> Ensure proper connection string configuration before calling

> [!NOTE]
> Reuses existing connection if already open

> [!TIP]
> Use callback for connection validation

> [!CAUTION]
> Connection timeout may occur on slow networks

> [!WARNING]
> Ensure proper error handling for production use

Handles graceful disconnection from database with transaction management and resource cleanup.

Features:
- Transaction commit/rollback handling
- Connection state management
- Resource cleanup
- Method chaining support
- Error logging

Example Request:


{
  "commitTransaction": true
}



Example Usage:


var db = new PostgreHelper("connection_string");

// Basic usage
db.Connect()
  .ExecuteNonQuery(
    sql: "INSERT INTO Users (Name) VALUES (@name)",
    parameters: new { name = "John" },
    out _
  )
  .Disconnect(commitTransaction: true);

// With transaction handling
try
{
    db.Connect(useTransaction: true)
      .ExecuteNonQuery(
        sql: "INSERT INTO Users (Name) VALUES (@name)",
        parameters: new { name = "John" },
        out _
      )
      .Disconnect(commitTransaction: true);
}
catch
{
    db.Disconnect(commitTransaction: false);
    throw;
}



> [!IMPORTANT]
> Ensure all operations are complete before disconnecting

> [!NOTE]
> Automatically handles transaction rollback if commitTransaction is false

> [!TIP]
> Use in try-catch block for proper transaction handling

> [!CAUTION]
> Active queries will be terminated on disconnect

> [!WARNING]
> Uncommitted transactions will be lost

Handles active transaction before disconnecting asynchronously.
Commits transaction if specified.
Closes database connection.
Executes callback if provided after successful disconnection.

Features:
- Asynchronous disconnection
- Optional transaction commit
- Connection state cleanup
- Optional callback execution
- Cancellation support
- Error handling and logging

Example Request:


{
  "commitTransaction": true,
  "callback": "optional_action_after_disconnect",
  "cancellationToken": "optional_cancellation_token"
}



Example Usage:


// Basic disconnection
await db.DisconnectAsync();

// With transaction commit
await db.DisconnectAsync(
    commitTransaction: true
);

// Advanced usage with callback and cancellation
var cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
await db.DisconnectAsync(
    commitTransaction: true,
    callback: _ => Console.WriteLine("Disconnected successfully"),
    cancellationToken: cts.Token
);

// Chain operations
await db.DisconnectAsync()
    .ContinueWith(task => {
        Console.WriteLine("Cleanup after disconnect");
    });



> [!IMPORTANT]
> Ensure all operations are complete before disconnecting

> [!NOTE]
> Uncommitted transactions will be rolled back unless commitTransaction is true

> [!TIP]
> Use callback for cleanup operations

> [!CAUTION]
> Active queries will be terminated

> [!WARNING]
> Connection pooling may keep connection alive

