Implements the IDisposable pattern for synchronous resource cleanup and management.
Ensures proper release of database connections and related resources.

Features:
- Synchronous resource cleanup
- Connection pool management
- Transaction handling
- Memory cleanup
- State management

Cleanup Process:
1. Validates disposal state
2. Rolls back any pending transactions
3. Closes active connections
4. Clears connection pool
5. Releases managed resources
6. Suppresses finalization

Example Request:

{
  "instance": "PostgreHelper instance to be disposed"
}


Example Usage:


// Using declaration (recommended)
using var db = new PostgreHelper(
    connectionString: "Host=localhost;Database=mydb"
);

// Manual disposal
var db = new PostgreHelper(
    connectionString: "Host=localhost;Database=mydb"
);
try
{
    db.Connect();
    // ... database operations
}
finally
{
    db.Dispose();
}



> [!IMPORTANT]
> Always dispose instances to prevent resource leaks

> [!NOTE]
> Implements standard IDisposable pattern

> [!TIP]
> Use 'using' statement for automatic disposal

> [!CAUTION]
> Ensure all operations are complete before disposal

> [!WARNING]
> Using disposed instance will throw ObjectDisposedException

Performs asynchronous cleanup of database resources and connections.
Implements IAsyncDisposable pattern for proper resource management.

Features:
- Asynchronous resource cleanup
- Connection pool management
- Transaction handling
- Memory cleanup
- State management

Cleanup Process:
1. Validates disposal state
2. Rolls back any pending transactions
3. Closes active connections
4. Clears connection pool
5. Releases managed resources

Example Request:

{
  "instance": "PostgreHelper instance to be disposed"
}


Example Usage:


// Using declaration (recommended)
await using var db = new PostgreHelper(
    connectionString: "Host=localhost;Database=mydb"
);

// Manual disposal
var db = new PostgreHelper(
    connectionString: "Host=localhost;Database=mydb"
);
try
{
    await db.Connect();
    // ... database operations
}
finally
{
    await db.DisposeAsync();
}



> [!IMPORTANT]
> Always await disposal to ensure proper cleanup

> [!NOTE]
> Implements both sync and async disposal patterns

> [!TIP]
> Use 'await using' for automatic disposal

> [!CAUTION]
> Ensure all operations are complete before disposal

> [!WARNING]
> Using disposed instance will throw ObjectDisposedException

Tracks the disposal state of the PostgreHelper instance to prevent use after disposal.
Used internally by the IDisposable implementation.

Features:
- Thread-safe disposal tracking
- Resource cleanup management
- Connection state validation
- Disposal status checking

Example Request:

{
  "_disposed": "Boolean flag indicating disposal state"
}


Example Usage:


public void Dispose()
{
    if (_disposed)
        return;

    _disposed = true;
    _connection?.Dispose();
}

private void ThrowIfDisposed()
{
    if (_disposed)
        throw new ObjectDisposedException(
            objectName: nameof(PostgreHelper)
        );
}



> [!IMPORTANT]
> Always check disposal state before performing operations

> [!NOTE]
> Set to true in Dispose() method

> [!TIP]
> Use ThrowIfDisposed() method to validate state

> [!CAUTION]
> Operations after disposal may throw ObjectDisposedException

> [!WARNING]
> This field should only be modified within disposal-related methods

Provides centralized message management for PostgreSQL operations.
Supports localization and custom message overrides.

Features:
- Customizable error messages
- Operation status messages
- Localization support
