> Ensure parameter types match the stored procedure signature

Internal method for synchronous connection management.
Opens connection if closed and optionally starts transaction.

Features:
- Synchronous connection handling
- Optional transaction support
- Connection state management
- Method chaining capability
- Automatic resource management

Example Request:

{
  "useTransaction": true,
  "disconnectFirst": false
}


Example Usage:


var db = CreateConnection(
  useTransaction: true,
  disconnectFirst: false
);

try
{
  db.ExecuteNonQuery(
    query: "INSERT INTO Users (Name) VALUES (@name)",
    affectedRows: out int rows
  )
  .Commit();
}
catch
{
  db.Rollback();
  throw;
}



> [!IMPORTANT]
> Ensure proper transaction handling (Commit/Rollback) when useTransaction is true

> [!NOTE]
> Connection state is preserved unless disconnectFirst is true

> [!TIP]
> For asynchronous operations, use CreateConnectionAsync instead

> [!CAUTION]
> Multiple active transactions are not supported

> [!WARNING]
> Ensure proper error handling and transaction management

Internal method for asynchronous connection management.
Opens connection if closed and optionally starts transaction.

Features:
- Asynchronous connection handling
- Optional transaction support
- Connection state management
- Cancellation support
- Method chaining capability

Example Request:

{
  "useTransaction": true,
  "disconnectFirst": false,
  "cancellationToken": "CancellationToken instance"
}


Example Usage:


var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

var db = await CreateConnectionAsync(
  useTransaction: true,
  disconnectFirst: false,
  cancellationToken: cts.Token
);

try
{
  // Perform database operations
  await db.CommitAsync();
}
catch
{
  await db.RollbackAsync();
  throw;
}



> [!IMPORTANT]
> Ensure proper transaction handling (Commit/Rollback) when useTransaction is true

> [!NOTE]
> Connection state is preserved unless disconnectFirst is true

> [!TIP]
> Use cancellationToken for timeout handling in long-running operations

> [!CAUTION]
> Multiple active transactions are not supported

> [!WARNING]
> Cancellation may leave the connection in an undefined state

example.code:
// Custom messages
var messages = new PostgreHelper.Messages
{
  MSG_CONNECTION_ESTABLISHED = "Koneksi ke database PostgreSQL telah dibuat.",
  MSG_TRANSACTION_STARTED = "Transaksi database telah dimulai.",
  MSG_ALREADY_DISPOSED = "PostgreHelper telah di-dispose."
};

// Usage with PostgreHelper
var db = new PostgreHelper(
  connectionString: "Host=localhost;Database=mydb;Username=user;Password=pass",
  messages: messages
);

// Custom disposal message
var messages = new PostgreHelper.Messages
{
  MSG_ALREADY_DISPOSED = "Database helper telah dinonaktifkan"
};

using var db = new PostgreHelper(
  connectionString: "Host=localhost;Database=mydb;Username=user;Password=pass",
  messages: messages
);

// Will throw ObjectDisposedException with custom message after this point
db.Dispose();

var messages = new PostgreHelper.Messages
{
  MSG_CONNECTION_ESTABLISHED = "Database connection established successfully"
};

var db = new PostgreHelper(
  connectionString: "Host=localhost;Database=mydb;Username=user;Password=pass",
  messages: messages
);

var messages = new PostgreHelper.Messages
{
  MSG_CONNECTION_NOT_ESTABLISHED = "Koneksi ke database belum dibuat"
};

var db = new PostgreHelper(
  connectionString: "Host=localhost;Database=mydb;Username=user;Password=pass",
  messages: messages
);

// This will throw an exception with the custom message
db.ExecuteNonQuery("SELECT 1", out _); // Error: Connection not established

var messages = new PostgreHelper.Messages
{
  MSG_TRANSACTION_NOT_STARTED = "Transaksi database belum dimulai"
};

var db = new PostgreHelper(
  connectionString: "Host=localhost;Database=mydb;Username=user;Password=pass",
  messages: messages
);

// This will throw an exception with the custom message
db.Connect()
  .TransactionCommit(); // Error: Transaction not started

var messages = new PostgreHelper.Messages
{
  MSG_TRANSACTION_STARTED = "Transaksi database sudah berjalan"
};

var db = new PostgreHelper(
  connectionString: "Host=localhost;Database=mydb;Username=user;Password=pass",
  messages: messages
);

// Second TransactionBegin will log warning with custom message
db.Connect()
  .TransactionBegin()
  .TransactionBegin(); // Warning: Transaction already started

member.remarks:
This class encapsulates the schema, stored procedure name, and parameters for executing
a PostgreSQL stored procedure.

Example usage:

var callInfo = new PostgreHelper.SPCallInfo
{
    Schema = "public",
    SPName = "my_procedure",
    Parameters = [new PostgreHelper.SPParameter().With(name: "param1", value: "value1")]
};

example.code:
var info = new PostgreHelper.SPCallInfo
{
    Schema = "finance",
    SPName = "calculate_interest",
    Parameters = [
        new PostgreHelper.SPParameter().With(name: "principal", value: 100000),
        new PostgreHelper.SPParameter().With(name: "rate", value: 0.05)
    ]
};

// Basic usage
db.Connect()
  .TransactionBegin()
  .ExecuteNonQuery(
    query: "INSERT INTO Users (Name) VALUES (@name)",
    parameters: new { name = "John" },
    out _
  )
  .TransactionCommit();

// With multiple operations
db.Connect()
  .TransactionBegin()
  .ExecuteNonQuery(
    query: "UPDATE Users SET Status = @status WHERE Id = @id",
    parameters: new { status = "active", id = 1 },
    out _
  )
  .ExecuteNonQuery(
    query: "INSERT INTO Logs (Action) VALUES (@action)",
    parameters: new { action = "User updated" },
    out _
  )
  .TransactionCommit();

// Basic usage
await db.Connect()
  .TransactionBeginAsync(
    cancellationToken: cts.Token
  );

// With callback
await db.TransactionBeginAsync(
  callback: helper => Console.WriteLine($"Transaction started on {helper._connection.Database}"),
  cancellationToken: cts.Token
);

// In transaction chain
await db.Connect()
  .TransactionBeginAsync(
    callback: helper => helper.ExecuteNonQuery(
      query: "SET TRANSACTION ISOLATION LEVEL SERIALIZABLE",
      out _
    ),
    cancellationToken: cts.Token
  );

// Basic usage
db.Connect()
  .TransactionBegin()
  .ExecuteNonQuery(
    query: "INSERT INTO Users (Name) VALUES (@name)",
    parameters: new { name = "John" }
  )
  .TransactionCommit(reinitTransactions: false);

// With reinitialization
db.Connect()
  .TransactionBegin()
  .ExecuteNonQuery(
    query: "UPDATE Users SET Status = @status WHERE Id = @id",
    parameters: new { status = "active", id = 1 }
  )
  .TransactionCommit(reinitTransactions: true)
  .ExecuteNonQuery(
    query: "INSERT INTO Logs (Action) VALUES (@action)",
    parameters: new { action = "User updated" }
  )
  .TransactionCommit();

// Basic usage
await db.Connect()
  .TransactionBeginAsync()
  .ExecuteNonQueryAsync(
    query: "INSERT INTO Users (Name) VALUES (@name)",
    parameters: new { name = "John" }
  )
  .TransactionCommitAsync(
    reinitTransactions: false,
    cancellationToken: cts.Token
  );

// With callback
await db.TransactionCommitAsync(
  reinitTransactions: true,
  callback: helper => Console.WriteLine($"Transaction committed on {helper._connection.Database}"),
  cancellationToken: cts.Token
);

// In transaction chain
await db.Connect()
  .TransactionBeginAsync()
  .ExecuteNonQueryAsync(
    query: "UPDATE Users SET Status = @status WHERE Id = @id",
    parameters: new { status = "active", id = 1 }
  )
  .TransactionCommitAsync(
    reinitTransactions: true,
    callback: helper => _logger.LogInformation("Transaction committed"),
    cancellationToken: cts.Token
  );

// Basic usage
db.Connect()
  .TransactionBegin()
  .ExecuteNonQuery(
    query: "INSERT INTO Users (Name) VALUES (@name)",
    parameters: new { name = "John" },
    rowsAffected: out int _
  )
  .TransactionRemove(
    commitTransaction: true,
    reinitTransactions: false
  );

// With error handling
try
{
  db.TransactionRemove(
    commitTransaction: true,
    reinitTransactions: true
  );
}
catch (Exception ex)
{
  // Handle errors
  _logger.LogError(
    message: "Failed to remove transaction",
    exception: ex
  );
}

// In transaction chain
db.Connect()
  .TransactionBegin()
  .ExecuteNonQuery(
    query: "UPDATE Users SET Status = @status WHERE Id = @id",
    parameters: new { status = "active", id = 1 },
    rowsAffected: out int affected
  )
  .TransactionRemove(commitTransaction: affected > 0)
  .Disconnect();

// Basic usage
await db.Connect()
  .TransactionBeginAsync()
  .ExecuteNonQueryAsync(
    query: "INSERT INTO Users (Name) VALUES (@name)",
    parameters: new { name = "John" })
  .TransactionRemoveAsync(
    commitTransaction: true,
    reinitTransactions: false);

// With callback and cancellation
var cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
await db.TransactionRemoveAsync(
  commitTransaction: true,
  reinitTransactions: true,
  callback: helper => Console.WriteLine(
    $"Transaction removed on {helper._connection.Database}"
  ),
  cancellationToken: cts.Token
);

// Error handling
try
{
  await db.TransactionRemoveAsync(
    commitTransaction: true,
    callback: helper => LogTransaction(helper)
  );
}
catch (OperationCanceledException)
{
  // Handle cancellation
}
catch (Exception ex)
{
  // Handle other errors
}

member.remarks:
Performs asynchronous transaction rollback with optional reinitialization:
- Rolls back active transaction asynchronously
- Optionally starts new transaction after rollback
- Executes callback if provided after successful rollback

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Ensure all pending operations are completed before rollback

> [!NOTE]
> If no transaction exists, method logs warning and returns immediately

> [!TIP]
> Use callback parameter for transaction-specific cleanup or logging

Example response body:

{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Transaction rolled back successfully",
  "details": {
    "reinitialized": false,
    "database": "mydb"
  }
}


Example:

// Basic usage
await db.Connect()
  .TransactionBeginAsync()
  .ExecuteNonQueryAsync(
    query: "INSERT INTO Users (Name) VALUES (@name)",
    parameters: new { name = "John" }
  )
  .TransactionRollbackAsync(
    reinitTransactions: false,
    cancellationToken: cts.Token
  );

// With callback
await db.TransactionRollbackAsync(
  reinitTransactions: true,
  callback: helper => Console.WriteLine($"Transaction rolled back on {helper._connection.Database}"),
  cancellationToken: cts.Token
);

// In transaction chain
await db.Connect()
  .TransactionBeginAsync()
  .ExecuteNonQueryAsync(
    query: "UPDATE Users SET Status = @status WHERE Id = @id",
    parameters: new { status = "active", id = 1 }
  )
  .TransactionRollbackAsync(
    reinitTransactions: true,
    callback: helper => _logger.LogInformation("Transaction rolled back"),
    cancellationToken: cts.Token
  );

Performs connection cleanup by:
- Closing active connection
- Clearing connection pool
- Disposing connection object

> [!IMPORTANT]
> This method should be called before disposing the helper instance

> [!NOTE]
> For async operations, use CleanupConnectionAsync() instead

> [!WARNING]
> Ensure all pending operations are completed before calling this method

Example cleanup sequence:

// Basic cleanup
db.CleanupConnection();

// Cleanup with error handling
try
{
    db.CleanupConnection();
}
catch (Exception ex)
{
    // Handle cleanup failure
    _logger.LogError(message: "Connection cleanup failed", exception: ex);
}

// Cleanup in using block
using (var db = new PostgreHelper(connectionString: "connection_string"))
{
    db.Connect();
    // Database operations
    db.CleanupConnection();
}

example.code:
// Cleanup with transaction
var db = new PostgreHelper(connectionString: "Host=localhost;Database=mydb");
db.Connect(useTransaction: true);

try
{
    db.ExecuteNonQuery(
        query: "INSERT INTO users (name) VALUES (@name)",
        parameters: new { name = "John" },
        rowsAffected: out int _
    );
    db.TransactionCommit();
}
finally
{
    db.CleanupConnection();
}

member.remarks:
Performs asynchronous connection cleanup by:
- Closing active connection asynchronously
- Clearing connection pool
- Disposing connection object asynchronously

> [!IMPORTANT]
> This method should be called before disposing the helper instance

> [!NOTE]
> Connection pool clearing is performed synchronously as it doesn't have an async counterpart

> [!WARNING]
> Ensure all pending operations are completed before calling this method

Example cleanup sequence:

// Basic cleanup
await db.CleanupConnectionAsync();

// Cleanup with error handling
try
{
    await db.CleanupConnectionAsync();
}
catch (Exception ex)
{
    // Handle cleanup failure
    _logger.LogError(message: "Connection cleanup failed", exception: ex);
}

// Cleanup in using block
await using (var db = new PostgreHelper(connectionString: "connection_string"))
{
    await db.ConnectAsync();
    // Database operations
    await db.CleanupConnectionAsync();
}

example.code:
// Async cleanup with transaction
var db = new PostgreHelper(connectionString: "Host=localhost;Database=mydb");
await db.ConnectAsync(useTransaction: true);

try
{
    await db.ExecuteNonQueryAsync(
        query: "INSERT INTO users (name) VALUES (@name)",
        parameters: new { name = "John" }
    );
    await db.TransactionCommitAsync();
}
finally
{
    await db.CleanupConnectionAsync();
}

var db = new PostgreHelper("connection_string");
if (db.ConnectionIsValid(out string statusMessage))
{
    Console.WriteLine("Connection is valid: " + statusMessage);
    // Proceed with database operations
}
else
{
    Console.WriteLine("Connection is invalid: " + statusMessage);
    // Handle connection issues
}

member.remarks:
Internal validation method to prevent operations on disposed instances.

This method is called before any operation that requires an active connection or transaction.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Always call this method before performing database operations

> [!NOTE]
> This method is part of the internal disposal tracking mechanism

> [!WARNING]
> Operations on disposed instances can lead to undefined behavior

Example validation sequence:

private void SomeOperation()
{
    try
    {
        ThrowIfDisposed();
        // Proceed with operation
    }
    catch (ObjectDisposedException ex)
    {
        _logging?.LogError(
            message: "Operation attempted on disposed instance",
            exception: ex
        );
        throw;
    }
}

example.code:
// Internal usage example
public PostgreHelper SomeOperation()
{
    ThrowIfDisposed();

    // Operation implementation
    var result = ExecuteSomeQuery();

    return this;
}

// With transaction handling
public PostgreHelper AnotherOperation()
{
    ThrowIfDisposed();

    if (_dbTrans != null)
    {
        // Transaction-specific logic
        _dbTrans.Save("checkpoint");
    }

    return this;
}

member.remarks:
Establishes a connection to the SQLite database and optionally initiates a transaction. This method is thread-safe and implements connection pooling for optimal performance.
Connection States: - If already connected: Returns immediately - If disconnected: Opens new connection - If transaction requested: Begins new transaction
Example request body for connection parameters:
{ "useTransaction": true, "connectionTimeout": 30, "commandTimeout": 30, "pooling": true }
Example usage:
using var db = new SQLiteHelper("Data Source=mydb.sqlite");
// Basic connection await db.Connect(useTransaction: false) .ExecuteQueryAsync( query: "SELECT * FROM Users", result: out List<User> users );
// With transaction await db.Connect(useTransaction: true) .ExecuteNonQueryAsync( query: "INSERT INTO Users (Name, Email) VALUES (@name, @email)", parameters: new { name = "John", email = "john@example.com" } ) .TransactionCommitAsync();
> [!IMPORTANT] > Always use transactions for operations that modify data
> [!TIP] > Use the 'using' statement to ensure proper resource cleanup
> [!NOTE] > Connection pooling is enabled by default for better performance

Safely closes the database connection while handling any active transactions. Provides options for transaction management before disconnection.
Disconnection Process: 1. Validates instance state 2. Handles active transaction (commit/rollback) 3. Closes database connection 4. Cleans up resources
Example request body:
{ "commitTransaction": true, "forceClose": false, "timeout": 30 }
Example usage:
using var db = new SQLiteHelper("Data Source=mydb.sqlite");
// Basic disconnection await db.Connect() .ExecuteQueryAsync( query: "SELECT * FROM Users", result: out List<User> users ) .Disconnect(commitTransaction: false);
// With transaction commit await db.Connect(useTransaction: true) .ExecuteNonQueryAsync( query: "UPDATE Users SET Status = @status WHERE Id = @id", parameters: new { status = "active", id = 1 } ) .Disconnect(commitTransaction: true);
> [!IMPORTANT] > Ensure all operations are complete before disconnecting
> [!WARNING] > Not committing an active transaction will result in automatic rollback
> [!TIP] > Use try-finally blocks for guaranteed disconnection in error scenarios

Forces a database reconnection by closing existing connection and establishing a new one. Provides option to start a new transaction after reconnection.
Reconnection Process: 1. Closes existing connection (if any) 2. Releases all resources 3. Establishes new connection 4. Optionally starts new transaction
Example request body:
{ "useTransaction": true, "connectionTimeout": 30, "retryAttempts": 3, "retryInterval": 1000 }
Example usage:
using var db = new SQLiteHelper("Data Source=mydb.sqlite");
// Basic reconnection await db.Reconnect(useTransaction: false) .ExecuteQueryAsync( query: "SELECT * FROM Users WHERE Status = @status", parameters: new { status = "active" }, result: out List<User> users );
// With transaction await db.Reconnect(useTransaction: true) .ExecuteNonQueryAsync( query: "UPDATE Products SET Stock = @stock WHERE Id = @id", parameters: new { stock = 100, id = 1 } ) .TransactionCommitAsync();
> [!IMPORTANT] > Any existing transaction will be rolled back during reconnection
> [!WARNING] > All prepared statements and temporary tables are lost after reconnection
> [!TIP] > Use this method to reset connection state or recover from connection errors
> [!CAUTION] > Ensure all operations are complete before reconnecting

Creates a new SQLiteHelper instance and immediately establishes database connection.
Example request body for connection string format:
{ "Data Source": "path/to/database.db", "Cache": "Shared", "Mode": "ReadWrite", "Password": "optional-password" }
Example usage:
using var db = new SQLiteHelper( connectionString: "Data Source=mydb.sqlite;Cache=Shared;Mode=ReadWrite", messages: new Messages(), logging: new SystemLogging() );
await db.ExecuteQueryAsync( query: "SELECT * FROM Users WHERE Age > @age", parameters: new { age = 18 }, result: out List<User> users );
> [!IMPORTANT] > Connection is opened automatically upon instantiation
> [!NOTE] > Use 'using' statement for automatic resource cleanup
> [!TIP] > For in-memory databases, consider using the dedicated constructor overload

Creates a new SQLiteHelper instance using a CommonConnectionString object and immediately opens the database
connection. This constructor provides a strongly-typed approach to database configuration.

Example request body for CommonConnectionString:


{
  "Database": "path/to/database.db",
  "Server": null,
  "Port": null,
  "Username": null,
  "Password": "optional-password",
  "Options": {
    "Cache": "Shared",
    "Mode": "ReadWrite"
  }
}



Example usage:


var connStr = new CommonConnectionString
{
    Database = "mydb.sqlite",
    Options = new Dictionary<string, string>
    {
        ["Cache"] = "Shared",
        ["Mode"] = "ReadWrite"
    }
};

using var db = new SQLiteHelper(
    connectionString: connStr,
    messages: new Messages(),
    logging: new SystemLogging()
);

await db.ExecuteQueryAsync(
    query: "SELECT * FROM Users",
    result: out List<User> users
);



> [!IMPORTANT]
> Connection is automatically established during instantiation

> [!TIP]
> Use this constructor when working with configuration-driven connection strings

> [!NOTE]
> The CommonConnectionString is automatically converted to SQLite format

Creates a new SQLiteHelper instance using an in-memory database with configurable caching behavior.
The in-memory database provides fast, temporary storage that exists only for the duration of the connection.

When cached is true:
- Multiple connections can access the same in-memory database
- Data persists as long as at least one connection remains open
- Useful for sharing data between different parts of the application

When cached is false:
- Each connection gets its own isolated database
- Data is completely private to the connection
- Useful for unit testing or temporary data processing

Example usage:


// Shared cache for multi-connection access
using var sharedDb = new SQLiteHelper(
    cached: true,
    messages: new Messages(),
    logging: new SystemLogging()
);
await sharedDb.ExecuteNonQueryAsync(
    query: "CREATE TABLE Users (Id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY, Name TEXT)"
);

// Private cache for isolated testing
using var privateDb = new SQLiteHelper(
    cached: false,
    logging: new SystemLogging()
);
await privateDb.ExecuteScalarAsync<int>(
    query: "SELECT COUNT(*) FROM sqlite_master"
);



> [!IMPORTANT]
> In-memory databases are volatile and data is lost when all connections are closed

> [!TIP]
> Use shared cache when multiple components need to access the same data

> [!CAUTION]
> Ensure proper connection management to prevent data loss in shared cache mode

Manages the connection lifecycle and state for SQLite database operations.
Provides thread-safe access to the underlying database.

Example usage:


using var connection = new SqliteConnection("Data Source=database.db");
connection.Open();

using var command = connection.CreateCommand();
command.CommandText = "SELECT * FROM Users";



> [!NOTE]
> Connection is initialized in constructor but not opened automatically

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Always dispose connection properly to release system resources

Provides centralized logging capabilities for SQLite operations including:
- Error tracking
- Performance monitoring
- Query execution details
- Connection state changes

Example request:

{
  "logLevel": "Information",
  "message": "Executing query: SELECT * FROM Users",
  "context": {
    "connectionId": "conn_123",
    "timestamp": "2024-01-20T10:30:00Z"
  }
}




// Initialize with logging
var logger = new SystemLogging();
var db = new SQLiteHelper(
    connectionString: "Data Source=app.db",
    logging: logger
);

// Logs will capture operations
db.Connect()
  .ExecuteNonQuery("CREATE TABLE Users (Id INT, Name TEXT)");



> [!NOTE]
> Logging is optional and can be disabled by passing null

> [!TIP]
> Enable logging during development for better debugging

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Sensitive data is automatically redacted from logs

Contains predefined messages for common scenarios including:
- Connection status messages
- Transaction state notifications
- Operation success/failure messages
- Warning and error messages



var messages = new Messages();
Console.WriteLine(messages.MSG_TRANSACTION_STARTED);
// Output: "Transaction already started"

Console.WriteLine(messages.MSG_CONNECTION_CLOSED);
// Output: "Connection is closed"



> [!NOTE]
> Messages can be customized by creating a new Messages instance

> [!TIP]
> Use these messages for consistent error handling and logging

Tracks the disposal state of the SQLiteHelper instance to prevent use after disposal.
Used internally by disposal pattern implementation.



private void SomeOperation()
{
    if (_disposed)
        throw new ObjectDisposedException(nameof(SQLiteHelper));

    // Proceed with operation
}



> [!IMPORTANT]
> Always check this flag before performing operations

> [!WARNING]
> Using disposed instance may result in ObjectDisposedException

This method allows you to create a user-defined SQL function that can be used in SQL queries executed against the SQLite database.
The function can have no parameters and returns a value of type TResult.
The isDeterministic parameter indicates whether the function always produces the same result for the same input values.
If set to true, SQLite may optimize calls to the function.
See https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/standard/data/sqlite/user-defined-functions for more information.


var dbHelper = new SQLiteHelper("Data Source=mydatabase.db");
dbHelper.Connect();
dbHelper.CreateFunction<int>(
    functionName: "GetRandomNumber",
    function: () => new Random().Next(),
    isDeterministic: false
);

This method allows you to create a user-defined SQL function that can be used in SQL queries executed against the SQLite database.
The function takes one parameter of type T1 and returns a value of type TResult.
The isDeterministic parameter indicates whether the function always produces the same result for the same input values.
If set to true, SQLite may optimize calls to the function.
See https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/standard/data/sqlite/user-defined-functions for more information.


var dbHelper = new SQLiteHelper("Data Source=mydatabase.db");
dbHelper.Connect();
dbHelper.CreateFunction<int, int>(
    functionName: "Square",
    function: x => x * x,
    isDeterministic: true
);

This method allows you to create a user-defined SQL function that can be used in SQL queries executed against the SQLite database.
The function takes two parameters of types T1 and T2 and returns a value of type TResult.
The isDeterministic parameter indicates whether the function always produces the same result for the same input values.
If set to true, SQLite may optimize calls to the function.
See https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/standard/data/sqlite/user-defined-functions for more information.


var dbHelper = new SQLiteHelper("Data Source=mydatabase.db");
dbHelper.Connect();
dbHelper.CreateFunction<int, int, int>(
   functionName: "Add",
  function: (x, y) => x + y,
  isDeterministic: true
);

This method allows you to create a user-defined SQL function that can be used in SQL queries executed against the SQLite database.
The function can take a variable number of parameters and returns a value of type object?.
The isDeterministic parameter indicates whether the function always produces the same result for the same input values.
If set to true, SQLite may optimize calls to the function.


var dbHelper = new SQLiteHelper("Data Source=mydatabase.db");
dbHelper.Connect();
dbHelper.CreateFunction(
    functionName: "ConcatStrings",
   function: args => string.Join(", ", args.Select(arg => arg?.ToString() ?? "NULL")),
   isDeterministic: true
);

Executes SQL commands that modify the database (INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE) and returns affected row count. Supports transaction management and proper error handling.
Example request:
{ "query": "INSERT INTO Users (Name, Email, Age) VALUES (@name, @email, @age)", "parameters": { "name": "John Doe", "email": "john@example.com", "age": 30 } }
// Single operation var db = new SQLiteHelper(connectionString: "Data Source=users.db"); db.Connect() .ExecuteNonQuery( query: "INSERT INTO Users (Name, Email) VALUES (@name, @email)", affectedRows: out int insertedRows ) .Disconnect();
// Multiple operations in transaction db.Connect() .TransactionBegin() .ExecuteNonQuery( query: "UPDATE Users SET Status = @status WHERE Age > @age", affectedRows: out int updatedRows ) .ExecuteNonQuery( query: "DELETE FROM Logs WHERE Timestamp < @oldDate", affectedRows: out int deletedRows ) .TransactionCommit() .Disconnect();
> [!IMPORTANT] > Always use parameterized queries to prevent SQL injection attacks
> [!NOTE] > For batch operations, consider wrapping multiple calls in a transaction
> [!TIP] > Use the returned instance for method chaining with other operations
> [!CAUTION] > Ensure proper error handling and transaction management for data consistency
> [!WARNING] > Large batch operations may impact database performance

Supports transaction management and proper error handling.
Example request:
{ "query": "INSERT INTO Users (Name, Email) VALUES (@name, @email)", "parameters": { "name": "John Doe", "email": "john@example.com" } }
// Single operation var db = new SQLiteHelper(connectionString: "Data Source=users.db"); db.Connect() .ExecuteNonQuery( query: "INSERT INTO Users (Name, Email) VALUES (@name, @email)", parameters: new { name = "John Doe", email = "john@example.com" }, affectedRows: out int insertedRows ) .Disconnect();
// Multiple operations in transaction db.Connect() .TransactionBegin() .ExecuteNonQuery( query: "UPDATE Users SET Status = @status WHERE Age > @age", parameters: new { status = "Active", age = 18 }, affectedRows: out int updatedRows ) .ExecuteNonQuery( query: "DELETE FROM Logs WHERE Timestamp < @oldDate", parameters: new { oldDate = DateTime.Now.AddDays(-30) }, affectedRows: out int deletedRows ) .TransactionCommit() .Disconnect();
> [!IMPORTANT] > Always use parameterized queries to prevent SQL injection attacks
> [!NOTE] > For batch operations, consider wrapping multiple calls in a transaction
> [!TIP] > Use the returned instance for method chaining with other operations
> [!CAUTION] > Ensure proper error handling and transaction management for data consistency
> [!WARNING] > Large batch operations may impact database performance

Provides JSON-formatted access to query results using .
Optimized for JSON data representation and serialization.

Example request:

{
  "query": "SELECT Id, Name, Email FROM Users WHERE Department = @dept",
  "parameters": {
    "dept": "Engineering"
  }
}




var db = new SQLiteHelper(connectionString: "Data Source=users.db");

// Basic JSON access
db.Connect()
  .ExecuteQuery(
    query: "SELECT Name, Email FROM Users",
    results: out List<JObject> usersJson
  );

foreach (var user in usersJson)
{
    var name = user["Name"]?.ToString();
    var email = user["Email"]?.ToString();
    Console.WriteLine($"{name}: {email}");
}

// Using with type conversion
db.Connect()
  .ExecuteQuery(
    query: "SELECT Id, Age, IsActive FROM Users",
    results: out List<JObject> typedJson
  );

foreach (var user in typedJson)
{
    var id = user["Id"]?.Value<int>();
    var age = user["Age"]?.Value<int?>();
    var isActive = user["IsActive"]?.Value<bool>();
}



> [!IMPORTANT]
> Each row is converted to a JObject with column names as properties

> [!NOTE]
> Null values are preserved in the JSON structure

> [!TIP]
> Use strong typing with Value<T>() for type-safe access

> [!CAUTION]
> Always check for null values before accessing properties

Executes a SQL query using parameterized query to prevent SQL injection attacks and returns results as a list of , where each JObject represents a row with properties corresponding to column names and values. Supports method chaining and automatic resource disposal.
Features: - Synchronous execution - Method chaining - Automatic resource disposal - Transaction support - Error logging
Example Request:
{ "query": "SELECT Name, Email FROM Users WHERE Age > @age", "parameters": { "age": 18 } }
Example Usage:
var db = new SQLiteHelper(connectionString: "Data Source=users.db");
db.Connect() .ExecuteQuery( query: "SELECT Name, Email FROM Users WHERE Age > @age", parameters: new Dictionary<string, object> { { "age", 18 } }, results: out var users ) .Disconnect();
foreach (var user in users) { Console.WriteLine($"{user["Name"]}: {user["Email"]}"); }
> [!IMPORTANT] > Ensure proper disposal of the instance after use.
> [!NOTE] > Null values are preserved in the JSON structure.
> [!TIP] > Use strong typing with Value<T>() for type-safe access.
> [!CAUTION] > Always check for null values before accessing properties.

Provides table-formatted access to query results using a .
Optimized for structured data representation and manipulation.

Example request:

{
  "query": "SELECT Id, Name, Email FROM Users WHERE Department = @dept",
  "parameters": {
    "dept": "Engineering"
  }
}




var db = new SQLiteHelper(connectionString: "Data Source=users.db");

// Basic table access
db.Connect()
  .ExecuteQuery(
    query: "SELECT Name, Email FROM Users",
    results: out DataTable usersTable
  );

foreach (DataRow row in usersTable.Rows)
{
    var name = row["Name"].ToString();
    var email = row["Email"].ToString();
    Console.WriteLine($"{name}: {email}");
}

// Using with type conversion
db.Connect()
  .ExecuteQuery(
    query: "SELECT Id, Age, IsActive FROM Users",
    results: out DataTable typedTable
  );

foreach (DataRow row in typedTable.Rows)
{
    var id = Convert.ToInt32(row["Id"]);
    var age = row["Age"] == DBNull.Value
        ? null
        : Convert.ToInt32(row["Age"]);
    var isActive = Convert.ToBoolean(row["IsActive"]);
}



> [!IMPORTANT]
> Dispose DataTable after use to release memory resources

> [!NOTE]
> DataTable loads entire result set into memory

> [!TIP]
> Use column names for better code readability

> [!CAUTION]
> Check for DBNull before accessing nullable columns

Provides forward-only, read-only access to query results using a .
Optimized for memory efficiency when processing large result sets.

Example request:

{
  "query": "SELECT Id, Name, Email FROM Users WHERE Department = @dept",
  "parameters": {
    "dept": "Engineering"
  }
}




var db = new SQLiteHelper(connectionString: "Data Source=users.db");

// Basic row iteration
db.Connect()
  .ExecuteReader(
    query: "SELECT Name, Email FROM Users",
    reader: out var dataReader
  );

while (dataReader.Read())
{
    var name = dataReader.GetString(columnName: "Name");
    var email = dataReader.GetString(columnName: "Email");
    Console.WriteLine($"{name}: {email}");
}

// Using with type checking
db.Connect()
  .ExecuteReader(
    query: "SELECT Id, Age, IsActive FROM Users",
    reader: out var typedReader
  );

while (typedReader.Read())
{
    var id = typedReader.GetInt32(columnName: "Id");
    var age = typedReader.IsDBNull(columnName: "Age")
        ? null
        : typedReader.GetInt32(columnName: "Age");
    var isActive = typedReader.GetBoolean(columnName: "IsActive");
}



> [!IMPORTANT]
> Reader must be closed after use to release database resources

> [!NOTE]
> Connection must remain open while reader is in use

> [!TIP]
> Use GetOrdinal() to get column index by name for better performance

> [!CAUTION]
> Always check for DBNull before accessing nullable columns

Executes a SQL query with parameters and returns a  for row-by-row access to the result set.
Supports method chaining and automatic resource disposal.

Features:
- Synchronous execution
