Provides a centralized collection of customizable text messages used throughout SQLite operations.
These messages can be modified at runtime to support:
- Multiple languages (localization)
- Custom error handling
- Logging requirements
- Debugging information

> [!NOTE]
> All messages can be modified after initialization to support different languages or custom requirements

> [!TIP]
> Consider using a resource file for better localization management

Example message customization:


using var db = new SQLiteHelper(connectionString: "Data Source=mydb.sqlite");

// Customize connection message
db.Messages.MSG_CONNECTION_ESTABLISHED = "Database connected successfully";

// Customize multiple messages
db.Messages = new Messages
{
    MSG_CONNECTION_ESTABLISHED = "Connected to SQLite",
    MSG_CONNECTION_NOT_ESTABLISHED = "Connection failed",
    MSG_TRANSACTION_STARTED = "Transaction began",
    MSG_TRANSACTION_NOT_STARTED = "No active transaction",
    MSG_ALREADY_DISPOSED = "Instance disposed"
};

This message is used in logging and diagnostic outputs to indicate that an operation was attempted
on a SQLiteHelper instance that has already been disposed.

> [!WARNING]
> Accessing disposed instances can lead to ObjectDisposedException and resource leaks

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Always check disposal state using  before performing operations

> [!TIP]
> Use 'using' statements or try-finally blocks to ensure proper resource cleanup

Example usage:


await using (var db = new SQLiteHelper(connectionString: "Data Source=mydb.sqlite"))
{
    db.Messages.MSG_ALREADY_DISPOSED = "Instance disposed at {timestamp}. Operation: {operation}";
    await db.ConnectAsync(cancellationToken: cancellationToken);
    // Perform operations
} // Automatically disposes

try
{
    // This will trigger the message since the instance is disposed
    await db.ExecuteQueryAsync(
        sql: "SELECT * FROM Users",
        parameters: null,
        cancellationToken: cancellationToken
    );
}
catch (ObjectDisposedException ex)
{
    _logger.LogError(
        message: db.Messages.MSG_ALREADY_DISPOSED,
        args: new[] { DateTime.UtcNow, "ExecuteQuery" }
    );
}

This message is used in logging and diagnostic outputs to indicate that a connection to the SQLite database
has been successfully established and is ready for operations.

> [!NOTE]
> This message is typically logged at Information level

> [!TIP]
> Include connection details like database path or connection mode for better diagnostics

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Ensure connection string parameters are properly sanitized before logging

Example usage:


// Basic connection with logging
var db = new SQLiteHelper(connectionString: "Data Source=mydb.sqlite");
db.Messages.MSG_CONNECTION_ESTABLISHED = "Connected to {database} in {mode} mode at {timestamp}";

try
{
    await db.ConnectAsync(cancellationToken: cancellationToken);
    _logger.LogInformation(
        message: db.Messages.MSG_CONNECTION_ESTABLISHED,
        args: new[] { "mydb.sqlite", "ReadWrite", DateTime.UtcNow }
    );

    // With connection validation
    if (await db.IsConnectedAsync(cancellationToken: cancellationToken))
    {
        await db.ExecuteNonQueryAsync(
            sql: "CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS Users (Id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY, Name TEXT)",
            parameters: null,
            cancellationToken: cancellationToken
        );
    }
}
catch (SqliteException ex)
{
    await db.DisconnectAsync(cancellationToken: cancellationToken);
}
finally
{
    await db.DisposeAsync();
}

This message is used in logging and diagnostic outputs to indicate connection failures or missing connections to the SQLite database.
The message can be customized for different languages or specific logging requirements.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> This message is typically logged at Error level and may contain sensitive connection information

> [!TIP]
> Consider including error details or connection parameters for debugging purposes

> [!CAUTION]
> Avoid including sensitive information like passwords in production environments

Example usage:


var db = new SQLiteHelper(connectionString: "Data Source=mydb.sqlite");
db.Messages.MSG_CONNECTION_NOT_ESTABLISHED = "Failed to connect to database at {path}. Error: {error}";

try
{
    await db.ConnectAsync(cancellationToken: cancellationToken);
}
catch (SqliteException ex)
{
    _logger.LogError(
        message: db.Messages.MSG_CONNECTION_NOT_ESTABLISHED,
        args: new[] { "mydb.sqlite", ex.Message }
    );
}

This message is used in logging and diagnostic outputs to indicate that a transaction-related operation
cannot be performed because no transaction is currently active in the session.

> [!WARNING]
> Transaction operations like commit or rollback will fail if no transaction is active

> [!TIP]
> Always check for active transactions using  before
> performing transaction operations

> [!IMPORTANT]
> This message is typically logged at Error level as it indicates a potential programming error

Example usage:


var db = new SQLiteHelper(connectionString: "Data Source=mydb.sqlite");
db.Messages.MSG_TRANSACTION_NOT_STARTED = "No active transaction found. Operation: {operation}";

try
{
    await db.ConnectAsync(cancellationToken: cancellationToken);

    // This will trigger the message since no transaction is active
    await db.TransactionCommitAsync(cancellationToken: cancellationToken);
}
catch (InvalidOperationException ex)
{
    _logger.LogError(
        message: db.Messages.MSG_TRANSACTION_NOT_STARTED,
        args: new[] { "Commit" }
    );

    // Proper transaction handling
    if (!db.HasActiveTransaction)
    {
        await db.TransactionBeginAsync(cancellationToken: cancellationToken);
        // Perform operations
        await db.TransactionCommitAsync(cancellationToken: cancellationToken);
    }
}

This message is used in logging and diagnostic outputs to indicate that a new transaction cannot be started
because there is an existing active transaction in the current session.

> [!WARNING]
> Multiple active transactions are not supported in SQLite

> [!TIP]
> Always commit or rollback existing transactions before starting new ones

> [!NOTE]
> This message is typically logged at Warning level

Example usage:


var db = new SQLiteHelper(connectionString: "Data Source=mydb.sqlite");
db.Messages.MSG_TRANSACTION_STARTED = "Transaction already exists. ID: {transactionId}";

try
{
    await db.ConnectAsync(cancellationToken: cancellationToken);
    await db.TransactionBeginAsync(cancellationToken: cancellationToken);

    // This will trigger the message since a transaction is already active
    await db.TransactionBeginAsync(cancellationToken: cancellationToken);
}
catch (InvalidOperationException ex)
{
    _logger.LogWarning(
        message: db.Messages.MSG_TRANSACTION_STARTED,
        args: new[] { db.CurrentTransactionId }
    );
    await db.TransactionRollbackAsync(cancellationToken: cancellationToken);
}

Initiates a new SQLite transaction for atomic database operations. The transaction ensures data consistency and can be either committed or rolled back.
Key Features: - Prevents creation of multiple transactions - Automatically logs warnings for duplicate transaction attempts - Supports method chaining for fluent API usage
Example usage:
// Basic transaction db.Connect() .TransactionBegin() .ExecuteNonQuery(sql: "INSERT INTO Users (Name) VALUES ('John')", rowsAffected: out _) .TransactionCommit();
// Multiple operations in single transaction db.Connect() .TransactionBegin() .ExecuteNonQuery(sql: "INSERT INTO Users (Name) VALUES ('John')", rowsAffected: out _) .ExecuteNonQuery(sql: "UPDATE Logs SET Status = 'Active'", rowsAffected: out _) .TransactionCommit();
> [!IMPORTANT] > Always ensure transactions are either committed or rolled back to prevent resource leaks
> [!NOTE] > Transactions are automatically rolled back if not explicitly committed
> [!TIP] > Use transactions when performing multiple related database operations that must succeed or fail together

Commits the active transaction and optionally starts a new one. This method ensures data persistence while maintaining transaction flow control.
Key Features: - Atomic commit operation - Optional transaction restart - Automatic resource cleanup - Method chaining support
Example usage:
// Basic commit db.Connect() .TransactionBegin() .ExecuteNonQuery(sql: "INSERT INTO Users (Name, Age) VALUES (@Name, @Age)", parameters: new { Name = "John", Age = 30 }, rowsAffected: out _) .TransactionCommit(reinitTransactions: false);
// Commit with transaction restart db.Connect() .TransactionBegin() .ExecuteNonQuery(sql: "INSERT INTO Users (Name, Age) VALUES (@Name, @Age)", parameters: new { Name = "John", Age = 30 }, rowsAffected: out _) .TransactionCommit(reinitTransactions: true) .ExecuteNonQuery(sql: "INSERT INTO Logs (UserId, Action) VALUES (@UserId, @Action)", parameters: new { UserId = 1, Action = "Created" }, rowsAffected: out _) .TransactionCommit();
> [!IMPORTANT] > Ensure all data modifications are complete before committing
> [!NOTE] > If no transaction exists, a warning will be logged and the method will return safely
> [!TIP] > Use reinitTransactions when you need to immediately start a new transaction after commit
> [!CAUTION] > Committing large transactions may temporarily lock the database

Manages transaction lifecycle by providing options to commit, remove, and restart transactions. This method offers fine-grained control over transaction handling and resource management.
Key Features: - Optional transaction commit before removal - Automatic resource cleanup - Optional transaction restart - Method chaining support - Thread-safe operation
Example usage:
// Remove without commit db.Connect() .TransactionBegin() .ExecuteNonQuery(sql: "INSERT INTO Users (Name, Age) VALUES (@Name, @Age)", parameters: new { Name = "John", Age = 30 }, rowsAffected: out _) .TransactionRemove(commitTransaction: false);
// Remove with commit and restart db.Connect() .TransactionBegin() .ExecuteNonQuery(sql: "INSERT INTO Users (Name, Age) VALUES (@Name, @Age)", parameters: new { Name = "John", Age = 30 }, rowsAffected: out _) .TransactionRemove(commitTransaction: true, reinitTransactions: true) .ExecuteNonQuery(sql: "INSERT INTO Logs (Action) VALUES (@Action)", parameters: new { Action = "Transaction removed" }, rowsAffected: out _) .TransactionCommit();
> [!IMPORTANT] > Uncommitted changes will be lost if commitTransaction is false
> [!NOTE] > If no transaction exists, a warning will be logged and method returns safely
> [!TIP] > Use this method when you need to reset transaction state without explicit commit/rollback
> [!CAUTION] > Ensure all operations are complete before removing active transactions
> [!WARNING] > Transaction removal without commit will discard all pending changes

Performs a rollback of the active transaction and optionally initiates a new transaction. This method ensures data integrity by reverting all changes made within the current transaction scope.
Key Features: - Complete transaction rollback - Optional automatic transaction restart - Automatic resource cleanup - Method chaining support - Thread-safe operation
Example usage:
// Basic rollback db.Connect() .TransactionBegin() .ExecuteNonQuery(sql: "INSERT INTO Users (Name, Age) VALUES (@Name, @Age)", parameters: new { Name = "John", Age = 30 }, rowsAffected: out _) .TransactionRollback(reinitTransactions: false);
// Rollback with transaction restart db.Connect() .TransactionBegin() .ExecuteNonQuery(sql: "INSERT INTO Users (Name, Age) VALUES (@Name, @Age)", parameters: new { Name = "John", Age = 30 }, rowsAffected: out _) .TransactionRollback(reinitTransactions: true) .ExecuteNonQuery(sql: "INSERT INTO Logs (Action) VALUES (@Action)", parameters: new { Action = "Rollback performed" }, rowsAffected: out _) .TransactionCommit();
> [!IMPORTANT] > All changes within the transaction scope will be discarded upon rollback
> [!NOTE] > If no active transaction exists, a warning will be logged and method returns safely
> [!TIP] > Use reinitTransactions when you need to start a new transaction immediately after rollback
> [!CAUTION] > Ensure all resources are properly handled before rolling back large transactions
> [!WARNING] > Rolling back a transaction cannot be undone

Performs comprehensive cleanup of database connection resources in the following order:
- Checks and closes any active connection
- Clears the connection pool to free memory
- Properly disposes the connection object

Example usage:


var db = new SQLiteHelper("Data Source=mydb.sqlite");
try
{
    db.Connect();
    // Perform database operations
}
finally
{
    db.CleanupConnection();
}



> [!IMPORTANT]
> Always call this method in a finally block to ensure proper resource cleanup

> [!NOTE]
> This method is thread-safe and can be called multiple times safely

> [!WARNING]
> Any ongoing transactions will be rolled back when cleanup is performed

