Provides type-safe string conversion with support for multiple data types and null handling.

Supported conversions:
- Any object (using ToString())
- Existing string (direct return)
- Null to default value

Example Request:

{
  "value": 42,
  "defaultValue": "N/A"
}




// Basic number conversion
int number = 42;
string? result1 = number.CastToString(); // returns "42"

// DateTime conversion
DateTime date = DateTime.Now;
string? result2 = date.CastToString(); // returns current date as string

// Handling null with default
object? nullObj = null;
string? result3 = nullObj.CastToString(defaultValue: "N/A"); // returns "N/A"

// Custom object conversion
var person = new Person { Name = "John", Age = 30 };
string? result4 = person.CastToString(); // returns person.ToString()

// Collection conversion
var list = new List<int> { 1, 2, 3 };
string? result5 = list.CastToString(); // returns "System.Collections.Generic.List`1[System.Int32]"

// Chaining with other extensions
int? nullableNumber = 42;
string? result6 = nullableNumber
    .Map(mapper: n => n * 2)
    .CastToString(defaultValue: "Invalid");





> [!NOTE]
> Handles null values gracefully by returning the specified default value

> [!TIP]
> Use with custom objects by overriding their ToString() method

> [!IMPORTANT]
> All primitive types are supported out of the box

> [!CAUTION]
> Complex objects may need custom ToString() implementation

> [!WARNING]
> Collection types may return their type name instead of contents

Provides type-safe TimeSpan conversion with support for multiple data types and null handling.

Supported conversions:
- String to TimeSpan ("01:30:00", "1.02:03:04.005", "30.00:00:00")
- Long to TimeSpan (ticks)
- Integer to TimeSpan (seconds)
- Double to TimeSpan (seconds)
- Existing TimeSpan (direct return)
- Null to default value

Example Request:

{
  "value": "01:30:00",
  "defaultValue": "00:00:00"
}




// Standard format string conversion
string timeStr = "01:30:00";
TimeSpan? result1 = timeStr.CastToTimeSpan(); // returns 1.5 hours

// Days format string conversion
string daysStr = "1.02:03:04.005";
TimeSpan? result2 = daysStr.CastToTimeSpan(); // returns 1 day, 2 hours, 3 minutes, 4 seconds, 5 ms

// Long (ticks) conversion
long ticks = 150000000000; // 15 seconds in ticks
TimeSpan? result3 = ticks.CastToTimeSpan(); // returns 15 seconds

// Integer (seconds) conversion
int seconds = 90;
TimeSpan? result4 = seconds.CastToTimeSpan(); // returns 1.5 minutes

// Double (seconds) conversion
double dblSeconds = 45.5;
TimeSpan? result5 = dblSeconds.CastToTimeSpan(); // returns 45.5 seconds

// Handling null with default
string? nullTime = null;
TimeSpan? result6 = nullTime.CastToTimeSpan(defaultValue: TimeSpan.Zero);

// Invalid conversion with default
string invalid = "not-a-time";
TimeSpan? result7 = invalid.CastToTimeSpan(defaultValue: TimeSpan.FromMinutes(minutes: 5));

// Chaining with other extensions
string? input = "00:30:00";
string? result8 = input
    .CastToTimeSpan()
    .Map(mapper: ts => ts.Add(TimeSpan.FromMinutes(minutes: 15)))
    .Map(mapper: ts => ts.ToString(format: @"hh\:mm\:ss"));



> [!NOTE]
> Handles null values gracefully by returning the specified default value

> [!TIP]
> Supports multiple time formats including days notation

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Integer and double values are interpreted as seconds

> [!CAUTION]
> Culture-specific time formats may affect string parsing

> [!WARNING]
> Invalid time strings will return the default value

Provides a safe way to execute actions on non-null values while maintaining a fluent interface.

Key Features:
- Null-safe operation
- Fluent interface support
- Thread-safe execution
- Generic type support
- Action delegation

Example Request:

{
  "value": {
    "id": 1,
    "name": "John Doe",
    "email": "john@example.com"
  },
  "action": "LogUserAccess"
}




// Basic usage
User? user = GetUser();
user.IfNotNull(action: u => Console.WriteLine(u.Name));

// Method chaining
string? input = "Hello World";
var result = input
    .IfNotNull(action: s => Console.WriteLine($"Processing: {s}"))
    .IfNotNull(action: s => Logger.Log($"Value: {s}"))
    .Map(mapper: s => s.ToUpper());

// With complex operations
DatabaseConnection? connection = GetConnection();
connection
    .IfNotNull(action: conn => conn.Open())
    .IfNotNull(action: conn => ExecuteQuery(conn))
    .IfNotNull(action: conn => conn.Close());

// Multiple operations
Customer? customer = GetCustomer();
customer
    .IfNotNull(action: c => ValidateCustomer(c))
    .IfNotNull(action: c => UpdateLastAccess(c))
    .IfNotNull(action: c => NotifyCustomerService(c));



> [!NOTE]
> The action is only executed if the value is not null

> [!TIP]
> Useful for logging, validation, and side effects without breaking the method chain

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The original value is always returned, regardless of the action's result

> [!CAUTION]
> Actions should not modify the input value to maintain predictability

> [!WARNING]
> Exceptions in the action will propagate to the caller

Provides a functional approach to transform values from one type to another using a mapping function.

Key Features:
- Type-safe transformation
- Functional programming support
- Fluent interface design
- Thread-safe operation
- Chainable with other extensions

Example Request:

{
  "value": {
    "id": 1,
    "name": "John Doe"
  },
  "mapper": "ToUserDto"
}




// Basic type conversion
int number = 42;
string result = number.Map(mapper: x => x.ToString());

// Object transformation
User user = new User { Id = 1, Name = "John" };
UserDto dto = user.Map(mapper: u => new UserDto
{
    Id = u.Id,
    DisplayName = u.Name
});

// Collection transformation
List<int> numbers = new() { 1, 2, 3 };
List<string> strings = numbers
    .Map(mapper: nums => nums.Select(n => n.ToString()).ToList());

// Chaining transformations
string input = "42";
double result = input
    .Map(mapper: s => int.Parse(s))
    .Map(mapper: i => i * 2)
    .Map(mapper: i => Convert.ToDouble(i));



> [!NOTE]
> This method is commonly used for DTO transformations and type conversions

> [!TIP]
> Can be chained with other Map calls for complex transformations

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The mapper function should be pure to maintain predictability

> [!CAUTION]
> Ensure mapper handles edge cases appropriately

> [!WARNING]
> Exceptions from the mapper function will propagate to the caller

Provides a fluent interface for null checking with custom error messages and parameter names.

Key Features:
- Fluent interface design
- Custom error messages
- Thread-safe operation
- Generic type support
- Chainable with other extensions

Example Request:

{
  "value": null,
  "paramName": "userId",
  "message": "User ID cannot be null"
}




// Basic usage
string? name = null;
string result = name.ThrowIfNull(paramName: "name");
// Throws: ArgumentNullException: Value cannot be null. (Parameter 'name')

// With custom message
User? user = null;
User result = user.ThrowIfNull(
    paramName: "user",
    message: "User object must be provided"
);
// Throws: ArgumentNullException: User object must be provided (Parameter 'user')

// In method chain
string? input = "Hello";
var result = input
    .ThrowIfNull(paramName: "input")
    .ToUpper()
    .Trim();
// Returns: "HELLO"

// With complex types
CustomObject? obj = null;
var result = obj.ThrowIfNull(paramName: "obj");
// Throws: ArgumentNullException: Value cannot be null. (Parameter 'obj')



> [!NOTE]
> This method is commonly used at the start of methods to validate parameters

> [!TIP]
> Use in conjunction with the null-conditional operator (?.) for safer null handling

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The generic constraint ensures type safety for reference types

> [!CAUTION]
> This method will always throw for null values, use IfNotNull for conditional execution

> [!WARNING]
> Value types should use ThrowIfDefault instead of this method

Provides a fluent interface for null or whitespace checking with custom error messages and parameter names.

Example Request:

{
  "value": "   ",
  "paramName": "username",
  "message": "Username cannot be empty"
}




// Basic usage
string? username = "   ";
string result = username.ThrowIfNullOrWhitespace(paramName: "username");
// Throws: ArgumentNullException: Value cannot be null or whitespace. (Parameter 'username')

// With custom message
string? email = "";
string result = email.ThrowIfNullOrWhitespace(
    paramName: "email",
    message: "Email address is required"
);
// Throws: ArgumentNullException: Email address is required (Parameter 'email')

// In method chain
string? input = "Hello";
var result = input
    .ThrowIfNullOrWhitespace(paramName: "input")
    .ToUpper()
    .Trim();
// Returns: "HELLO"



> [!NOTE]
> This method is commonly used to validate string parameters for null or whitespace.

> [!TIP]
> Use in conjunction with ThrowIfNull for comprehensive validation.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The method throws for both null and whitespace values.

> [!CAUTION]
> This method will always throw for invalid values, use IfNotNull for conditional execution.

> [!WARNING]
> Value types should use ThrowIfDefault instead of this method.

Provides a safe way to parse values with built-in error handling and default value support.

Key Features:
- Type-safe conversion
- Built-in error handling
- Default value support
- Thread-safe operation
- Chainable with other extensions

Example Request:

{
  "value": "42",
  "parser": "IntegerParser",
  "defaultValue": 0
}




// Basic integer parsing
string number = "42";
int result = number.TryParse(
    parser: s => (int.TryParse(s, out int n), n),
    defaultValue: 0
);

// Custom type parsing
string json = "{\"id\": 1, \"name\": \"John\"}";
UserDto user = json.TryParse(
    parser: s => {
        try {
            var obj = JsonSerializer.Deserialize<UserDto>(s);
            return (obj != null, obj ?? new UserDto());
        }
        catch {
            return (false, new UserDto());
        }
    },
    defaultValue: new UserDto()
);

// Chaining with other extensions
string input = "123.45";
int result = input
    .TryParse(
        parser: s => (double.TryParse(s, out double n), n),
        defaultValue: 0.0
    )
    .Map(mapper: d => (int)Math.Round(d));

// Custom parsing logic
string hex = "FF";
int decimal = hex.TryParse(
    parser: s => {
        try {
            return (true, Convert.ToInt32(s, 16));
        }
        catch {
            return (false, 0);
        }
    },
    defaultValue: 0
);



> [!NOTE]
> This method is commonly used for safe type conversion with error handling

> [!TIP]
> Can be combined with Map and other extensions for complex transformations

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Parser function should handle all possible error cases

> [!CAUTION]
> Ensure appropriate default values are provided for your use case

> [!WARNING]
> Exceptions in the parser function will be caught and result in the default value

This class contains utility methods for working with JObjects from Newtonsoft.Json.Linq.

Features:
