This method replaces a specified portion of a string with mask characters while preserving the original
length. It safely handles null inputs and validates index boundaries to prevent exceptions.

Example usage:


string creditCard = "1234567890123456";
string result1 = creditCard.Mask(startIndex: 6, length: 6);           // returns "123456******3456"

string email = "user@example.com";
string result2 = email.Mask(startIndex: 2, length: 4, maskChar: '#'); // returns "us####@example.com"

string phone = "1234567890";
string result3 = phone.Mask(startIndex: 3, length: 4);                // returns "123****890"

string nullString = null;
string result4 = nullString.Mask(startIndex: 0, length: 5);           // returns ""

// Invalid indices return original string
string text = "Hello";
string result5 = text.Mask(startIndex: 10, length: 2);               // returns "Hello"



> [!NOTE]
> The method preserves characters outside the masked region

> [!TIP]
> Useful for hiding sensitive information like credit card numbers or personal data

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Returns original string if start index or length are invalid

This method calculates the MD5 hash of the input string. It concatenates the input
string with the provided key before hashing. MD5 is a widely used hash function,
but it is considered cryptographically weak and should not be used for secure
applications.

> [!NOTE]
> The method returns null if the input string is null or empty.

> [!CAUTION]
> Ensure that the key is securely generated and stored to maintain the integrity
> of the hash.



string data = "example";
string key = "myKey";
string hash = data.AsMD5(key: key);
// Returns "e4d909c290d0fb1ca068ffaddf22cbd0"

This method decrypts a base64 encoded string using the RSA algorithm. The private key,
provided in XML format, is used to decrypt the cipher text. The decrypted data
is then converted to a UTF-8 string.

> [!NOTE]
> The private key must be in XML format and compatible with the .NET RSA implementation.

> [!CAUTION]
> RSA decryption should be used judiciously, as it is computationally intensive.
> Ensure the private key is securely managed to prevent unauthorized decryption.



string privateKey = "<RSAKeyValue><Modulus>...</Modulus><D>...</D></RSAKeyValue>";
string cipherText = "KTFmKRyc9jKa4mKy...";
string plainText = cipherText.AsRSADecrypt(privateKey: privateKey);
// Returns "example"

This method encrypts the input string using the RSA algorithm. The public key,
provided in XML format, is used to encrypt the plain text. The encrypted data
is then converted to a base64 string for easy storage or transmission.

> [!NOTE]
> The public key must be in XML format and compatible with the .NET RSA implementation.

> [!CAUTION]
> RSA encryption should be used judiciously, as it is computationally intensive.
> Ensure the public key is securely managed to prevent unauthorized encryption.



string publicKey = "<RSAKeyValue><Modulus>...</Modulus><Exponent>AQAB</Exponent></RSAKeyValue>";
string plainText = "example";
string cipherText = plainText.AsRSAEncrypt(publicKey: publicKey);
// Returns "KTFmKRyc9jKa4mKy...""

This method calculates the SHA-0 hash of the input string. It concatenates the input string
with the provided key before hashing. SHA-0 is an early version of the SHA family
of hash functions and has known security weaknesses.

> [!WARNING]
> SHA-0 is considered cryptographically broken and should not be used for secure applications.
> This method is provided for legacy support only.

> [!NOTE]
> The method returns null if the input string is null or empty.



string data = "example";
string key = "myKey";
string hash = data.AsSHA0(key: key);
// Returns "da39a3ee5e6b4b0d3255bfef95601890afd80709"

This method calculates the SHA-1 hash of the input string. It concatenates the input string
with the provided key and salt before hashing. SHA-1 is a widely used hash function,
though it has been superseded by stronger algorithms due to security concerns.

> [!WARNING]
> SHA-1 is considered cryptographically weak and should not be used for secure applications.
> This method is provided for legacy support only.

> [!NOTE]
> The method returns null if the input string is null or empty.



string data = "example";
string key = "myKey";
string salt = "mySalt";
string hash = data.AsSHA1(key: key, salt: salt);
// Returns "3c7963469f89464ca1f49111b71498f4c11a4a76"

This method calculates the SHA-224 hash of the input string. It concatenates the input
string with the provided key and salt before hashing. SHA-224 is a member of the SHA-2
family of hash functions and provides a 224-bit hash value.

> [!NOTE]
> The method returns null if the input string is null or empty.

> [!WARNING]
> While SHA-224 is more secure than SHA-1 and SHA-0, ensure it meets your application's
> security requirements. Consider using stronger SHA-2 variants like SHA-256 or SHA-512
> for sensitive applications.



string data = "example";
string key = "myKey";
string salt = "mySalt";
string hash = data.AsSHA224(key: key, salt: salt);
// Returns "4d4ee783146b996789687e32528488c1dca43444334ca96bda644dd6"

This method calculates the SHA-256 hash of the input string. It concatenates the input
string with the provided key and salt before hashing. SHA-256 is a member of the SHA-2
family of hash functions and is widely used for its strong security properties.

> [!NOTE]
> The method returns null if the input string is null or empty.

> [!CAUTION]
> Ensure that the key and salt are securely generated and stored to maintain the
> integrity of the hash.



string data = "example";
string key = "myKey";
string salt = "mySalt";
string hash = data.AsSHA256(key: key, salt: salt);
// Returns "2692bce46e55649aa942439ff586954532970aa9c6a34a143974ca9c7c962963"

This method calculates the SHA-384 hash of the input string. It concatenates the input
string with the provided key and salt before hashing. SHA-384 is a member of the SHA-2
family of hash functions and provides a 384-bit hash value.

> [!NOTE]
> The method returns null if the input string is null or empty.

> [!CAUTION]
> Ensure that the key and salt are securely generated and stored to maintain the
> integrity of the hash.



string data = "example";
string key = "myKey";
string salt = "mySalt";
string hash = data.AsSHA384(key: key, salt: salt);
// Returns "5922fa9544c93b428941d999869891cb2aa91f152f5c90bca9e367e68466ca9c6c7a97f534ca1ded95b9991ba9e30993"

This method calculates the SHA-512 hash of the input string. It concatenates the input
string with the provided key and salt before hashing. SHA-512 is a member of the SHA-2
family of hash functions and provides a 512-bit hash value, offering a high level of
security.

> [!NOTE]
> The method returns null if the input string is null or empty.

> [!CAUTION]
> Ensure that the key and salt are securely generated and stored to maintain the
> integrity of the hash.



string data = "example";
string key = "myKey";
string salt = "mySalt";
string hash = data.AsSHA512(key: key, salt: salt);
// Returns "f764c9ff7099c9649948527993369a92dd260a869f936a4547b116b9054c3c447b9c3b8a4a99dca3c77efc5bd6ca49583946c9db53d9c9c1ca65c31ca963f1b6"

This method calculates a cryptographic hash of the input data using the specified algorithm.
The resulting hash is converted to a lowercase hexadecimal string representation.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The method returns null if the input byte array is empty (length = 0).

> [!NOTE]
> The hash computation is performed synchronously. For large inputs, consider using
> asynchronous alternatives to avoid potential thread blocking.



byte[] data = Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes("example");
using var sha256 = SHA256.Create();
string hash = HashAlgorithm(inputBytes: data, algorithm: sha256);
// Returns "50d858e0985ecc7f60418aaf0cc5ab587f42c2570a884095a9e8ccacd0f6545c"

This method rotates the bits of the input value to the left by the specified number of bits.
The rotation is circular, meaning bits shifted off the left end are reintroduced on the right.

> [!NOTE]
> The method assumes a 32-bit unsigned integer input and performs modulo 32 on the bit count.



uint result = LeftRotate(value: 0b11001100110011001100110011001100, bits: 4);
// result will be 0b10011001100110011001100110011000

This class implements secure file-based encryption operations supporting multiple encryption methods: - AES (Advanced Encryption Standard) - DES (Data Encryption Standard) - RSA (Rivest-Shamir-Adleman) - Base64 Encoding
> [!IMPORTANT] > All encryption methods automatically handle key padding and validation. > Keys will be adjusted to the required length using the '#' character.
> [!WARNING] > Store encryption keys securely and never expose them in code or configuration files.
Example usage:
// AES Encryption var encryption = new FileEncryption(); await encryption.AESFileEncryption( sourceFileLocation: "source.txt", destFileLocation: "encrypted.aes", key: "MySecretKey1234", iv: "InitVector123456" );
// DES Encryption await encryption.DESFileEncryption( sourceFileLocation: "source.txt", destFileLocation: "encrypted.des", key: "MySecretKey" );

This class implements secure file-based encryption operations supporting multiple encryption methods: - AES (Advanced Encryption Standard) - DES (Data Encryption Standard) - RSA (Rivest-Shamir-Adleman) - Base64 Encoding
> [!IMPORTANT] > All encryption methods automatically handle key padding and validation. > Keys will be adjusted to the required length using the '#' character.
> [!WARNING] > Store encryption keys securely and never expose them in code or configuration files.
Example usage:
// AES Encryption var encryption = new FileEncryption(); await encryption.AESFileEncryption( sourceFileLocation: "source.txt", destFileLocation: "encrypted.aes", key: "MySecretKey1234", iv: "InitVector123456" );
// DES Encryption await encryption.DESFileEncryption( sourceFileLocation: "source.txt", destFileLocation: "encrypted.des", key: "MySecretKey" );

Provides functionality to load, update, and manage JSON data stored in a file.
The JSON structure can be hierarchical and can be accessed using dot notation.

Features:
- Thread-safe data access and updates
- Hierarchical data organization using dot notation
- Configurable logging
- Automatic resource cleanup

Example JSON structure:

{
  "en": {
    "greeting": "Hello",
    "errors": {
      "notfound": "Not found",
      "validation": "Invalid input"
    }
  },
  "id": {
    "greeting": "Halo",
    "errors": {
      "notfound": "Tidak ditemukan",
      "validation": "Input tidak valid"
    }
  }
}


> [!IMPORTANT]
> Always dispose of JsonFileProcessor instances when they are no longer needed to prevent resource leaks.

> [!TIP]
> Use the using statement for automatic disposal:

using (var jsonFile = new JsonFileProcessor("messages.json"))
{
    var message = jsonFile.GetMessage(
        language: "id",
        path: "greeting"
    );
}

Internal validation method to prevent operations on disposed instances.

Example usage:

private void SomeOperation()
{
    ThrowIfDisposed();
    // Proceed with operation
}

This method calls Dispose(disposing: true) to free managed resources
and suppresses finalization.


using (var jsonFile = new JsonFileProcessor("messages.json"))
{
    var message = jsonFile.GetMessage(
        language: "id",
        path: "greeting"
    );
}

Loads JSON data from the specified file and sets up logging.


using (var jsonFile = new JsonFileProcessor(filePath: "messages.json"))
{
    var message = jsonFile.GetMessage(language: "id", path: "greeting");
}

Retrieves a value from the JSON data using the provided path. If the path does not exist,
the method returns the specified default value.


var value = jsonFile.Get<string>(
    path: "en.greeting",
    defaultValue: "Default"
);

Retrieves a value from the JSON data using the provided path. If the path does not exist,
the method returns null.


var value = jsonFile.Get<string>(
    path: "en.greeting"
);

If the path exists, its value is updated; otherwise, a new entry is created.


var updatedJson = jsonFile.Upsert(
    path: "en.greeting",
    value: "Hello, world!"
);

Applies each key-value pair in the updates dictionary to the JSON structure.
If a key exists, its value is updated; otherwise, a new entry is created.


var updates = new Dictionary<string, object?>
{
    { "en.greeting", "Hello, world!" },
    { "id.greeting", "Halo, dunia!" }
};
var updatedJson = jsonFile.Upsert(updates: updates);

Deletes the entry at the given dot notation path from the JSON structure.
If the path does not exist, no action is taken.


var updatedJson = jsonFile.Remove(
    path: "en.greeting"
);

Writes the in-memory JSON structure to disk, overwriting the existing file.
jsonFile.SaveToFile();
> [!IMPORTANT] > > Ensure you have write permissions to the target file path.

Provides functionality to load, update, and manage language messages stored in JSON format.
The JSON structure should follow the pattern: { "languageCode": { "message.path": "value" } }.

Features:
- Thread-safe message access and updates
- Hierarchical message organization using dot notation
- Fallback to default language when message not found
- File-based or in-memory configuration
- Automatic resource cleanup

Example JSON structure:

{
  "en": {
    "greeting": "Hello",
    "errors": {
      "notfound": "Not found",
      "validation": "Invalid input"
    }
  },
  "id": {
    "greeting": "Halo",
    "errors": {
      "notfound": "Tidak ditemukan",
      "validation": "Input tidak valid"
    }
  }
}


> [!IMPORTANT]
> Always dispose of Language instances when they are no longer needed to prevent resource leaks.

> [!TIP]
> Use the using statement for automatic disposal:

using (var lang = new Language("messages.json"))
{
    var message = lang.GetMessage(
        path: "errors.notfound",
        language: "id"
    );
    Console.WriteLine(message); // Outputs: "Tidak ditemukan"
}

member.example:
Basic usage:

// Initialize with file
using var lang = new Language(
    jsonPath: "messages.json",
    defaultLanguage: "en"
);

// Get messages
string welcome = lang.GetMessage(path: "greeting", language: "id");
string error = lang.GetMessage(path: "errors.validation");

// Update messages
lang.UpdateMessage(
    language: "en",
    path: "new.key",
    value: "New Value"
);

// Save changes
lang.SaveToFile();

member.remarks:
Initialized to "en" by default. Used as fallback when:
- No language is specified in GetMessage calls
- Requested language doesn't have the specified message

Example structure:

{
  "en": {              // _defaultLanguage = "en"
    "greeting": "Hi"   // Fallback message
  },
  "id": { }           // If "greeting" not found here, uses "en" version
}

Loads and parses language messages from a JSON file. The JSON structure should follow the pattern:

{
  "en": {
    "messages.welcome": "Welcome",
    "errors.notfound": "Not found"
  },
  "id": {
    "messages.welcome": "Selamat datang",
    "errors.notfound": "Tidak ditemukan"
  }
}


> [!NOTE]
> The file must exist and contain valid JSON data.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Make sure the JSON file is properly encoded in UTF-8 to support all characters.

Example usage:

try
{
    var lang = new Language(
        jsonPath: "path/to/messages.json",
        defaultLanguage: "en"
    );
    // Language instance ready to use
}
catch (FileNotFoundException ex)
{
    // Handle missing file
}
catch (JsonException ex)
{
    // Handle invalid JSON
}

Initializes language support using an existing JObject configuration.
Useful for in-memory language management without file dependencies.

Expected JObject structure:

{
  "en": {
    "messages": {
      "welcome": "Welcome",
      "goodbye": "Goodbye"
    }
  },
  "id": {
    "messages": {
      "welcome": "Selamat datang",
      "goodbye": "Selamat tinggal"
    }
  }
}


> [!NOTE]
> This constructor doesn't support file operations like SaveToFile() unless explicitly set later.

> [!TIP]
> Use this constructor when working with dynamic or programmatically generated language data.

Returns all configured language codes from the messages configuration.

Example usage:

var lang = new Language("messages.json");
string[] languages = lang.GetAvailableLanguages();
foreach (var code in languages)
{
    Console.WriteLine($"Supported language: {code}");
}

// Example output:
// Supported language: en
// Supported language: id
// Supported language: fr


> [!NOTE]
> Returns empty array if no languages are configured.

Retrieves a localized message using dot notation path. Falls back to default language if message not found in specified language.

Path structure examples:

// Simple paths
"welcome"              // -> messages.welcome
"errors.notfound"      // -> messages.errors.notfound
"validation.required"  // -> messages.validation.required

// Usage examples
var msg1 = GetMessage(path: "welcome", language: "id");
var msg2 = GetMessage(path: "errors.notfound");  // Uses default language
var msg3 = GetMessage(
    path: "validation.email",
    language: "fr"     // Falls back to default if French not found
);


> [!NOTE]
> If message is not found in specified language, falls back to default language.

> [!TIP]
> Returns the path itself if message not found in any language, useful for debugging.

Reloads language messages from the configured JSON file while preserving the current default language setting.
Useful for updating messages without restarting the application.

Example usage:

var lang = new Language("messages.json");

// After external file changes
if (lang.Reload())
{
    Console.WriteLine("Messages reloaded successfully");
}
else
{
    Console.WriteLine("Failed to reload messages");
}


> [!IMPORTANT]
> Ensure the file exists and is accessible before reloading.

> [!NOTE]
> The default language setting is preserved after reload.

> [!WARNING]
> Returns false if any error occurs during reload, including file access issues.

Writes the current state of language messages to the configured JSON file path.
The output is formatted with indentation for better readability.

Example output format:

{
  "en": {
    "messages": {
      "welcome": "Welcome",
      "goodbye": "Goodbye"
    }
  },
  "id": {
    "messages": {
      "welcome": "Selamat datang",
      "goodbye": "Selamat tinggal"
    }
  }
}


> [!IMPORTANT]
> Ensure the application has write permissions to the file location.

> [!NOTE]
> The file is saved using UTF-8 encoding to support international characters.

Example usage:

var lang = new Language("messages.json");
lang.UpdateMessage(
    language: "en",
    path: "greeting",
    value: "Hello",
    saveToFile: false
);
lang.SaveToFile(); // Explicitly save changes

Updates or creates a message at the specified path for the given language.
Uses dot notation to navigate nested structures.

Example paths:

// Simple path
UpdateMessage("en", "greeting", "Hello");

// Nested path
UpdateMessage("en", "errors.validation.required", "Field is required");

// With immediate save
UpdateMessage(
    language: "id",
    path: "messages.welcome",
    value: "Selamat datang",
    saveToFile: true
);


> [!IMPORTANT]
> If saveToFile is true but no file path is set, the save operation will be skipped without error.

> [!WARNING]
> Ensure proper error handling as this method returns false on any exception.

This class provides a consistent response format for API operations, including success and error scenarios.
It supports method chaining, localization, exception handling, and system logging integration.

Example response formats:

// Success Response
{
  "status": "Success",
  "message": "User profile updated successfully"
}

// Error Response
{
  "status": "Error",
  "message": "Database operation failed: Connection timeout"
}

// Validation Response
{
  "status": "Failed",
  "message": "Invalid input: Email address is required"
}


> [!NOTE]
> All response methods support method chaining for fluent API usage

> [!TIP]
> Use appropriate status values: "Success", "Failed", or "Error"

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Always handle sensitive information appropriately in error messages

> [!CAUTION]
> Stack traces should only be included in development environments

example.code:
// Basic usage
var response = new APIResponse()
    .ChangeStatus(status: "Success")
    .ChangeMessage(message: "Operation completed successfully");

// With localization
response.ChangeMessage(
    language: languageService,
    key: "api.messages.success"
);

// Error handling
try
{
    throw new DatabaseException("Connection failed");
}
catch (Exception ex)
{
    response
        .ChangeStatus(status: "Error")
        .ChangeMessage(
            exception: ex,
            logging: loggingService,
            includeStackTrace: false
        );
}

var response = new APIResponse()
    .ChangeMessage(message: "User profile updated successfully");

// Localized message
response.ChangeMessage(
    language: languageService,
    key: "api.messages.profile_updated"
);

// Exception handling
try
{
    throw new DbException("Connection failed");
}
catch (Exception ex)
{
    response.ChangeMessage(
        exception: ex,
        logging: loggingService,
        includeStackTrace: false
    );
}

member.remarks:
The default value is "Success". This property can be set using the 
method or its overloads.

Example usage:


var response = new APIResponse();

// Success case
response.Status = "Success";

// Failed case (business logic)
response.Status = "Failed";

// Error case (system error)
response.Status = "Error";



> [!NOTE]
> Status is automatically set to "Success" by default when creating a new instance

> [!TIP]
> Use the  method for localized status messages

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Status should reflect the actual outcome of the operation for proper error handling

example.code:
var response = new APIResponse();

// Success message
response.ChangeMessage(
    message: "User profile updated successfully"
);

// Validation error
response.ChangeMessage(
    message: "Invalid email format: user@example is not a valid email address"
);

// Not found error
response.ChangeMessage(
    message: "User with ID 12345 was not found"
);

member.remarks:
This method facilitates internationalization by allowing messages to be retrieved from language resource files. It's essential for building multilingual APIs.
Common key patterns:
Success messages: "api.messages.success"
Validation errors: "api.messages.validation.{field}"
Not found errors: "api.messages.notfound.{resource}"
System errors: "api.messages.system.error"
Example response formats:
// English Response { "status": "Success", "message": "User profile updated successfully" }
// Indonesian Response { "status": "Berhasil", "message": "Profil pengguna berhasil diperbarui" }
> [!NOTE] > Ensure all keys exist in the language resource files before using them
> [!TIP] > Organize keys hierarchically for better maintenance
> [!IMPORTANT] > Keep translations consistent across all supported languages
> [!WARNING] > Missing translations will throw KeyNotFoundException

example.code:
var response = new APIResponse();

// Basic usage
response.ChangeMessage(
    language: languageService,
    key: "api.messages.user.profile.updated"
);

// With different languages
response.ChangeMessage(
    language: indonesianLanguage,
    key: "api.messages.validation.email"
);

// Error messages
response.ChangeMessage(
    language: englishLanguage,
    key: "api.messages.error.notfound"
);

var response = new APIResponse();

try
{
    throw new InvalidOperationException("Database connection failed");
}
catch (Exception ex)
{
    // Basic usage - message only
    response.ChangeMessage(
        exception: ex,
        includeStackTrace: false
    );

    // With stack trace for debugging
    response.ChangeMessage(
        exception: ex,
        includeStackTrace: true
    );
}

var response = new APIResponse();
var logger = new SystemLogging();

try
{
    throw new DatabaseException("Failed to connect to database");
}
catch (Exception ex)
{
    // Basic usage with logging
    response.ChangeMessage(
        exception: ex,
        logging: logger,
        includeStackTrace: false
    );

    // With stack trace for detailed debugging
    response.ChangeMessage(
        exception: ex,
        logging: logger,
        includeStackTrace: true
    );
}

var response = new APIResponse();

// Success scenario
response.ChangeStatus(status: "Success");

// Business logic failure
response.ChangeStatus(status: "Failed");

// System error
response.ChangeStatus(status: "Error");

var response = new APIResponse();

// Success case with Indonesian language
response.ChangeStatus(
    language: languageService,
    key: "api.status.success"
);

// Error case with English language
response.ChangeStatus(
    language: englishLanguageService,
    key: "api.status.not_found"
);

member.remarks:
             Provides a consistent structure for API responses with status, message, and strongly-typed data handling.
             Inherits base functionality from  and adds generic data support.

             Response format patterns:


Single entity responses

Collection responses

Paginated data responses

Null data handling


             Example response formats:

             // Single Entity Response
             {
               "status": "Success",
               "message": "User retrieved successfully",
               "data": {
                 "id": "123",
                 "username": "johndoe",
                 "email": "john@example.com"
               }
             }

             // Collection Response
             {
               "status": "Success",
               "message": "Users retrieved successfully",
               "data": [
                 {
                   "id": "123",
                   "username": "johndoe"
                 },
                 {
                   "id": "124",
                   "username": "janedoe"
                 }
               ]
             }

             // Null Data Response
             {
               "status": "Success",
               "message": "No data found",
               "data": null
             }


             > [!NOTE]
             > All properties support null values for proper null handling

             > [!TIP]
             > Use appropriate data types for better type safety

             > [!IMPORTANT]
             > Always validate data before setting it in the response

             > [!CAUTION]
             > Ensure sensitive data is properly filtered before sending

example.code:
// Single entity response
var userResponse = new APIResponseData<UserModel>()
    .ChangeStatus(status: "Success")
    .ChangeMessage(message: "User retrieved successfully")
    .ChangeData(data: new UserModel
    {
        Id = "123",
        Username = "johndoe",
        Email = "john@example.com"
    });

// Collection response
var usersResponse = new APIResponseData<IEnumerable<UserModel>>()
    .ChangeStatus(status: "Success")
    .ChangeMessage(message: "Users retrieved successfully")
    .ChangeData(data: new[]
    {
        new UserModel { Id = "123", Username = "johndoe" },
        new UserModel { Id = "124", Username = "janedoe" }
    });

// Null data handling
var emptyResponse = new APIResponseData<UserModel>()
    .ChangeStatus(status: "Success")
    .ChangeMessage(message: "No user found")
    .ChangeData(data: null);

member.remarks:
             This property serves as the main data container for the API response. It supports any type that can be
             serialized to JSON, including complex objects, collections, and primitive types.

             Common usage patterns:


Single entity responses (e.g., UserModel)

Collection responses (e.g., IEnumerable<UserModel>)

Primitive type responses (e.g., string, int)

Complex nested object responses


             Example response structures:

             // Single Entity
             {
               "status": "Success",
               "message": "User retrieved",
               "data": {
                 "id": "123",
                 "name": "John Doe",
                 "email": "john@example.com"
               }
             }

             // Collection
             {
               "status": "Success",
               "message": "Users retrieved",
               "data": [
                 { "id": "123", "name": "John" },
                 { "id": "124", "name": "Jane" }
               ]
             }

             // Null Data
             {
               "status": "Success",
               "message": "No data found",
               "data": null
             }


             > [!NOTE]
             > The property is internally settable to maintain encapsulation

             > [!TIP]
             > Use the ChangeData method for fluent API support

             > [!IMPORTANT]
             > Ensure data is properly sanitized before setting

             > [!CAUTION]
             > Avoid storing sensitive information in this property

example.code:
// Single entity
var response = new APIResponseData<UserModel>();
response.Data = new UserModel
{
    Id = "123",
    Name = "John Doe",
    Email = "john@example.com"
};

// Collection
var collectionResponse = new APIResponseData<IEnumerable<UserModel>>();
collectionResponse.Data = new List<UserModel>
{
    new() { Id = "123", Name = "John" },
    new() { Id = "124", Name = "Jane" }
};

// Null data
var emptyResponse = new APIResponseData<UserModel>();
emptyResponse.Data = null;

// Single entity example
var response = new APIResponseData<UserModel>()
    .ChangeStatus(status: "Success")
    .ChangeMessage(message: "User retrieved successfully")
    .ChangeData(data: new UserModel
    {
        Id = "123",
        Name = "John Doe",
        Email = "john@example.com"
    });

// Collection example
var collectionResponse = new APIResponseData<IEnumerable<UserModel>>()
    .ChangeData(data: new List<UserModel>
    {
        new() { Id = "123", Name = "John" },
        new() { Id = "124", Name = "Jane" }
    });

// Null data example
var emptyResponse = new APIResponseData<UserModel>()
    .ChangeData(data: null);

// Basic message update
var response = new APIResponseData<UserModel>()
    .ChangeMessage(message: "User profile updated successfully");

// Combined with status and data
var fullResponse = new APIResponseData<UserModel>()
    .ChangeStatus(status: "Success")
    .ChangeMessage(message: "User created successfully")
    .ChangeData(data: new UserModel
    {
        Id = "123",
        Name = "John Doe",
        Email = "john@example.com"
    });

// Error message
var errorResponse = new APIResponseData<UserModel>()
    .ChangeStatus(status: "Error")
    .ChangeMessage(message: "Invalid user data provided");

// Clearing message
var clearMessage = new APIResponseData<UserModel>()
    .ChangeMessage(message: null);

// Initialize language instance
var languageInstance = new Language();

// Basic message translation
var response = new APIResponseData<UserModel>()
    .ChangeMessage(
        language: languageInstance,
        key: "api.messages.user.created"
    );

// Combined with other methods
var fullResponse = new APIResponseData<UserModel>()
    .ChangeStatus(
        language: languageInstance,
        key: "api.status.success"
    )
    .ChangeMessage(
        language: languageInstance,
        key: "api.messages.user.updated"
    )
    .ChangeData(data: new UserModel
    {
        Id = "123",
        Name = "John Doe",
        Email = "john@example.com"
    });

// Error message with localization
var errorResponse = new APIResponseData<UserModel>()
    .ChangeMessage(
        language: languageInstance,
        key: "api.messages.user.not_found"
    );

try
{
    // Some operation that might throw an exception
    throw new InvalidOperationException("An error occurred");
}
catch (Exception ex)
{
    // Basic exception handling
    var response = new APIResponseData<UserModel>()
        .ChangeMessage(
            exception: ex,
            includeStackTrace: false
        );

    // With status and stack trace
    var detailedResponse = new APIResponseData<UserModel>()
        .ChangeStatus(status: "Error")
        .ChangeMessage(
            exception: ex,
            includeStackTrace: true
        );

    // Combined with data
    var fullResponse = new APIResponseData<UserModel>()
        .ChangeStatus(status: "PartialSuccess")
        .ChangeMessage(
            exception: ex,
            includeStackTrace: false
        )
        .ChangeData(data: new UserModel
        {
            Id = "123",
            Name = "John Doe"
        });
}

try
{
    // Some operation that might throw an exception
    throw new InvalidOperationException("An error occurred");
}
catch (Exception ex)
{
    var logging = new SystemLogging();

    // Basic exception handling with logging
    var response = new APIResponseData<UserModel>()
        .ChangeMessage(
            exception: ex,
            logging: logging,
            includeStackTrace: false
        );

    // With custom status and data
    var fullResponse = new APIResponseData<UserModel>()
        .ChangeStatus(status: "Error")
        .ChangeMessage(
            exception: ex,
            logging: logging,
            includeStackTrace: true
        )
        .ChangeData(data: new UserModel
        {
            Id = "123",
            Name = "John Doe",
            LastError = ex.Message
        });
}

// Basic status update
var response = new APIResponseData<UserModel>()
    .ChangeStatus(status: "Success");

// Combined with other methods
var fullResponse = new APIResponseData<UserModel>()
    .ChangeStatus(status: "Success")
    .ChangeMessage(message: "User created successfully")
    .ChangeData(data: new UserModel
    {
        Id = "123",
        Name = "John Doe"
    });

// Error status
var errorResponse = new APIResponseData<UserModel>()
    .ChangeStatus(status: "Error")
    .ChangeMessage(message: "User not found");

// Initialize language instance
var languageInstance = new Language();

// Basic status translation
var response = new APIResponseData<UserModel>()
    .ChangeStatus(
        language: languageInstance,
        key: "api.status.success"
    );

// Combined with other methods
var fullResponse = new APIResponseData<UserModel>()
    .ChangeStatus(
        language: languageInstance,
        key: "api.status.success"
    )
    .ChangeMessage(
        language: languageInstance,
        key: "api.messages.user_created"
    )
    .ChangeData(data: new UserModel
    {
        Id = "123",
        Name = "John Doe"
    });

// Error status with localization
var errorResponse = new APIResponseData<UserModel>()
    .ChangeStatus(
        language: languageInstance,
        key: "api.status.not_found"
    );

member.remarks:
Provides a standardized way to handle connection strings across different database systems including MongoDB, Oracle, SQL Server, and PostgreSQL.
> [!NOTE] > All sensitive information like passwords are stored as plain text. Ensure proper security measures when handling connection strings.
> [!IMPORTANT] > Always validate connection parameters before using in production environments
Example connection strings for different databases: ```json // MongoDB "mongodb://username:password@localhost:27017/mydatabase"
// Oracle "(DESCRIPTION=(HOST=localhost)(PORT=1521)(SERVICE_NAME=orcl));User Id=system;Password=********"
// SQL Server "Server=localhost,1433;Database=master;User ID=sa;Password=********;TrustServerCertificate=True"
// PostgreSQL "Server=localhost;Port=5432;Database=postgres;User ID=postgres;Password=********" ```
var connStr = new CommonConnectionString { Server = server: "localhost", Port = port: 5432, Database = database: "mydatabase", Username = username: "myuser", Password = password: "mypassword", TrustServerCertificate = trustServerCertificate: true };

Creates a connection string with secure default values suitable for development environments.
> [!WARNING] > Default values are not recommended for production use
Default Configuration: ```json { "Server": "localhost", "Port": 0, "Database": ":memory:", "Username": "", "Password": "", "ConnectionTimeout": 30, "Pooling": true, "MinPoolSize": 1, "MaxPoolSize": 100, "TrustServerCertificate": true, "IntegratedSecurity": false, "ApplicationName": null } ```
// Create with defaults var defaultConn = new CommonConnectionString();
// Create and customize var customConn = new CommonConnectionString { Server = server: "prod-server", Database = database: "production-db", Username = username: "app-user", Password = password: "secure-password" };

Used to identify the application in database server logs and monitoring tools.



var conn = new CommonConnectionString
{
    ApplicationName = applicationName: "MyApp.API.Production"
};

Maximum time to wait for a connection before throwing an exception.
Default is 30 seconds.



var conn = new CommonConnectionString
{
    ConnectionTimeout = connectionTimeout: 60  // 1 minute timeout
};

Specifies the name of the database to use. For SQLite, this can be ":memory:" or a file path.



var conn = new CommonConnectionString
{
    Database = database: "northwind",           // Regular database
    // or
    Database = database: ":memory:",           // SQLite in-memory
    // or
    Database = database: "C:/data/mydb.sqlite" // SQLite file
};

When true, uses Windows credentials instead of username/password.
Only applicable for SQL Server connections.



var conn = new CommonConnectionString
{
    IntegratedSecurity = integratedSecurity: true,
    // Username and Password not needed when using Windows Auth
};

Maximum number of connections allowed in the pool. Default is 100.

> [!NOTE]
> Set based on your application's concurrent connection needs



var conn = new CommonConnectionString
{
    MaxPoolSize = maxPoolSize: 200  // Allow up to 200 connections
};

Minimum number of connections maintained in the pool. Default is 1.



var conn = new CommonConnectionString
{
    MinPoolSize = minPoolSize: 5  // Keep minimum 5 connections
};

The password credential for database login. Store securely and never in plain text in production.

> [!WARNING]
> Never hard-code passwords in source code



var conn = new CommonConnectionString
{
    Username = username: "db_user",
    Password = password: Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("DB_PASSWORD")
};

Enables connection reuse to improve performance. Default is true.

> [!TIP]
> Keep enabled for better performance in most scenarios



var conn = new CommonConnectionString
{
    Pooling = pooling: true,
    MinPoolSize = minPoolSize: 5,
    MaxPoolSize = maxPoolSize: 100
};

Specifies the server address where the database is hosted. Can be hostname, IP address, or instance name.



var conn = new CommonConnectionString
{
    Server = server: "db.example.com"  // hostname
    // or
    Server = server: "192.168.1.100"   // IP address
    // or
    Server = server: "MSSQLSERVER01"    // instance name
};

When true, bypasses SSL certificate validation. Use with caution in production.

> [!CAUTION]
> Setting this to true in production may expose your connection to security risks



var conn = new CommonConnectionString
{
    TrustServerCertificate = trustServerCertificate: true
};

The username credential for database login. Leave empty for Windows Authentication.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Ensure proper access rights are granted to this user in the database



var conn = new CommonConnectionString
{
    Username = username: "db_user",
    Password = password: "db_password"
};

Updates the  property with the provided new password value.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The new password must not be null or empty.



var connStr = new CommonConnectionString
{
    Username = username: "db_user",
    Password = password: "old_password"
};
connStr.ChangePassword(newPassword: "new_secure_password");
// connStr.Password is now "new_secure_password"

Supports common connection string formats with various key aliases.
Supported parameter mappings: ```json { "server": ["data source", "host", "contact points"], "database": ["initial catalog", "default keyspace"], "username": ["user id", "uid", "user"], "password": ["pwd"], "port": [], "integratedSecurity": ["trusted_connection"], "trustServerCertificate": ["trust server certificate"], "timeout": ["connection timeout", "connect timeout"], "applicationName": ["application"], "pooling": [], "minPoolSize": ["minimum pool size"], "maxPoolSize": ["maximum pool size"] } ```
> [!NOTE] > All keys are case-insensitive
> [!TIP] > For MongoDB URLs, use the format: mongodb://[username:password@]host[:port][/database]
Example:
var connStr = "Server=localhost;Database=mydb;User ID=user;Password=pass;Port=1433;"; var result = commonConnStr.FromConnectionString(connectionString: connStr);
// MongoDB URL var mongoConnStr = "mongodb://user:pass@localhost:27017/mydb"; var mongoResult = commonConnStr.FromConnectionString(connectionString: mongoConnStr);

This method generates a connection string compatible with Cassandra databases using the DataStax C# Driver.

> [!NOTE]
> The generated string includes SSL, connection timeout, and authentication parameters.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Ensure that the Server, Port, and Database properties are set before calling this method.



var connStr = new CommonConnectionString
{
    Server = server: "localhost",
    Port = port: 9042,
    Database = database: "mykeyspace",
    Username = username: "myuser",
    Password = password: "mypassword"
};
string cassandraConnStr = connStr.ToCassandra();
// Result: "Contact Points=localhost;Port=9042;Default Keyspace=mykeyspace;User ID=myuser;Password=mypassword;SSL=true;Connection Timeout=10"

This method generates a connection string compatible with Couchbase databases using the Couchbase .NET SDK.

> [!NOTE]
> The generated string includes SSL, connection timeout, and authentication parameters.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Ensure that the Server and Database properties are set before calling this method.



var connStr = new CommonConnectionString
{
    Server = server: "localhost",
    Port = port: 8091,
    Database = database: "mybucket",
    Username = username: "myuser",
    Password = password: "mypassword"
};
string couchbaseConnStr = connStr.ToCouchbase();
// Result: "couchbase://localhost?connection_timeout=30000&bucket_name=mybucket&ssl=true&username=myuser&password=mypassword"

This method generates a connection string compatible with MariaDB databases using the MariaDB Connector/NET.

> [!NOTE]
> The generated string includes SSL configuration and pool sizing parameters.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Ensure that the Server and Database properties are set before calling this method.



var connStr = new CommonConnectionString
{
    Server = server: "localhost",
    Port = port: 3306,
    Database = database: "mydb",
    Username = username: "myuser",
    Password = password: "mypassword"
};
string mariaDbConnStr = connStr.ToMariaDB();
// Result: "Server=localhost;Port=3306;Database=mydb;User ID=myuser;Password=mypassword;Connection Timeout=30;Pooling=True;Min Pool Size=1;Max Pool Size=100;SSL Mode=Required;Allow User Variables=true"

This method generates a connection string compatible with MongoDB databases.

> [!NOTE]
> The generated string includes retry writes, write concern, SSL, and connection timeout parameters.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Ensure that the Server, Port, and Database properties are set before calling this method.



var connStr = new CommonConnectionString
{
    Server = server: "localhost",
    Port = port: 27017,
    Database = database: "mydb",
    Username = username: "myuser",
    Password = password: "mypassword",
    ConnectionTimeout = connectionTimeout: 30
};
string mongoDbConnStr = connStr.ToMongoDB();
// Result: "mongodb://myuser:mypassword@localhost:27017/mydb?retryWrites=true&w=majority&ssl=true&connectTimeoutMS=30000"

This method generates a connection string compatible with MySQL databases using the MySQL Connector/NET.

> [!NOTE]
> The generated string includes SSL configuration and pool sizing parameters.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Ensure that the Server and Database properties are set before calling this method.



var connStr = new CommonConnectionString
{
    Server = server: "localhost",
    Port = port: 3306,
    Database = database: "mydb",
    Username = username: "myuser",
    Password = password: "mypassword"
};
string mysqlConnStr = connStr.ToMySQL();
// Result: "Server=localhost;Port=3306;Database=mydb;User ID=myuser;Password=mypassword;Connection Timeout=30;Pooling=True;Min Pool Size=1;Max Pool Size=100;Allow User Variables=true;Convert Zero Datetime=true;SSL Mode=Required"

This method generates a connection string compatible with Oracle databases using Oracle Data Provider for .NET (ODP.NET).

> [!NOTE]
> The generated string includes Easy Connect Plus format and connection pooling parameters.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Ensure that the Server, Port, and Database (Service Name) properties are set before calling this method.



var connStr = new CommonConnectionString
{
    Server = server: "localhost",
    Port = port: 1521,
    Database = database: "ORCL",
    Username = username: "system",
    Password = password: "oracle"
};
string oracleConnStr = connStr.ToOracle();
// Result: "Data Source=(DESCRIPTION=(ADDRESS=(PROTOCOL=TCP)(HOST=localhost)(PORT=1521))(CONNECT_DATA=(SERVICE_NAME=ORCL)));User Id=system;Password=********;Pooling=true;Statement Cache Size=20"

This method generates a connection string compatible with PostgreSQL databases using the Npgsql provider.

> [!NOTE]
> The generated string includes SSL configuration and pool sizing parameters.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Ensure that the Server and Database properties are set before calling this method.



var connStr = new CommonConnectionString
{
    Server = server: "localhost",
    Port = port: 5432,
    Database = database: "mydb",
    Username = username: "myuser",
    Password = password: "mypassword"
};
string pgConnStr = connStr.ToPostgreSQL();
// Result: "Host=localhost;Port=5432;Database=mydb;Username=myuser;Password=mypassword;Timeout=30;Application Name=CommonConnectionString;Pooling=True;Minimum Pool Size=1;Maximum Pool Size=100;Trust Server Certificate=true"

This method generates a connection string compatible with SQLite databases.

> [!NOTE]
> The generated string includes cache and mode parameters.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Ensure that the Database property is set before calling this method.



var connStr = new CommonConnectionString
{
    Database = database: "C:/data/mydb.sqlite"
};
string sqliteConnStr = connStr.ToSQLite(cache: "Shared", mode: "ReadWrite");
// Result: "Data Source=C:/data/mydb.sqlite;Cache=Shared;Mode=ReadWrite"

This method generates a connection string for an in-memory SQLite database.

> [!NOTE]
> In-memory databases are temporary and exist only for the duration of the connection.

> [!TIP]
> Use shared cache to allow multiple connections to access the same in-memory database.

For more details about SQLite in-memory databases and cache modes, see:







var connStr = new CommonConnectionString();

// Create a shared in-memory database
string sharedMemoryDb = connStr.ToSQLiteInMemory(cached: true);
// Result: "Data Source=:memory:;Mode=Memory;Cache=Shared"

// Create a private in-memory database
string privateMemoryDb = connStr.ToSQLiteInMemory(cached: false);
// Result: "Data Source=:memory:;Mode=Memory;Cache=Private"

Supports standard MongoDB connection URL format with authentication and database name. Parses and validates all components of the connection string including: - Protocol (mongodb://) - Authentication credentials - Host(s) and port(s) - Database name - Connection options
Connection string components: - Protocol: mongodb:// or mongodb+srv:// - Credentials: username:password@ - Hosts: hostname1:port1,hostname2:port2 - Database: /database_name - Options: ?option1=value1&option2=value2
> [!IMPORTANT] > Connection string must follow MongoDB URL format specifications
> [!NOTE] > Special characters in username and password must be URL encoded
> [!TIP] > Use URI encoding for special characters in credentials
Example formats:
// Basic connection mongodb://localhost:27017/mydatabase
// With authentication mongodb://myuser:mypassword@localhost:27017/mydatabase
// With multiple hosts (replica set) mongodb://myuser:mypassword@host1:27017,host2:27017/mydatabase
// With query parameters mongodb://myuser:mypassword@localhost:27017/mydatabase?authSource=admin&ssl=true
// With connection pool settings mongodb://localhost:27017/mydatabase?maxPoolSize=50&waitQueueTimeoutMS=2000
// With replica set and read preference mongodb://host1:27017,host2:27017/mydatabase?replicaSet=mySet&readPreference=secondary

Supports Oracle TNS format with HOST, PORT, SERVICE_NAME parameters.

> [!NOTE]
> TNS format is commonly used for Oracle database connections

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Ensure all required TNS parameters are properly configured

Example formats:
```json
// Basic TNS format
"(DESCRIPTION=(HOST=myhost)(PORT=1521)(SERVICE_NAME=myservice))"

// With credentials
"(DESCRIPTION=(HOST=myhost)(PORT=1521)(SERVICE_NAME=myservice));User Id=myuser;Password=********"

// With multiple hosts
"(DESCRIPTION=(LOAD_BALANCE=on)
  (ADDRESS_LIST=
    (ADDRESS=(HOST=host1)(PORT=1521))
    (ADDRESS=(HOST=host2)(PORT=1521)))
  (SERVICE_NAME=myservice))"
```



var tnsString = "(DESCRIPTION=(HOST=dbhost)(PORT=1521)(SERVICE_NAME=orcl));User Id=system;Password=********";
var connStr = CommonConnectionString.ParseOracleTns(connectionString: tnsString);

// Results in:
// connStr.Server = "dbhost"
// connStr.Port = 1521
// connStr.Database = "orcl"
// connStr.Username = "system"
// connStr.Password = "oracle"

Handles various server:port formats including IPv6 addresses.

> [!NOTE]
> For IPv6 addresses, the address should be enclosed in square brackets



var connStr = new CommonConnectionString();

// Standard hostname:port
ParseServerValue(result: connStr, value: "localhost:5432");
// connStr.Server = "localhost"
// connStr.Port = 5432

// IPv6 address
ParseServerValue(result: connStr, value: "[2001:db8::1]:3306");
// connStr.Server = "2001:db8::1"
// connStr.Port = 3306

// Comma-separated format
ParseServerValue(result: connStr, value: "server1,1433");
// connStr.Server = "server1"
// connStr.Port = 1433

Converts milliseconds to seconds if "ms" suffix is present.
Returns 30 seconds as default if parsing fails.

> [!NOTE]
> Default timeout is 30 seconds



// Seconds format
var timeout1 = ParseTimeout(value: "60");     // Returns 60

// Milliseconds format
var timeout2 = ParseTimeout(value: "5000ms"); // Returns 5

// Invalid format
var timeout3 = ParseTimeout(value: "invalid"); // Returns 30 (default)

Handles various connection string parameter aliases across different database systems.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> All keys are normalized to lowercase before processing

Supported parameter mappings:
```json
{
  "server": ["data source", "host", "contact points"],
  "database": ["initial catalog", "default keyspace", "bucket_name", "databasename"],
  "username": ["user id", "uid", "user"],
  "password": ["pwd"],
  "integratedSecurity": ["trusted_connection"],
  "timeout": ["connection timeout", "connect timeout", "connection_timeout"],
  "poolSize": ["min pool size", "minimum pool size", "max pool size", "maximum pool size"]
}
```



var connStr = new CommonConnectionString();

// Server variations
ProcessKeyValuePair(result: connStr, key: "server", value: "localhost");
ProcessKeyValuePair(result: connStr, key: "data source", value: "localhost");
ProcessKeyValuePair(result: connStr, key: "host", value: "localhost");

// Authentication variations
ProcessKeyValuePair(result: connStr, key: "user id", value: "myuser");
ProcessKeyValuePair(result: connStr, key: "password", value: "mypass");
ProcessKeyValuePair(result: connStr, key: "integrated security", value: "true");

// Timeout and pooling
ProcessKeyValuePair(result: connStr, key: "connection timeout", value: "30");
ProcessKeyValuePair(result: connStr, key: "min pool size", value: "1");
ProcessKeyValuePair(result: connStr, key: "max pool size", value: "100");

Determines how many records to return per page. Defaults to 10.



var pageSize = request.Limit;
var pagedData = query.Take(pageSize);

Used to calculate the starting point for data retrieval.



var skipCount = request.Offset;
var data = dbContext.Users.Skip(skipCount);

Determines the sorting direction. Valid values are "asc" or "desc".



var isAscending = request.Order?.ToLower() == "asc";
var query = isAscending ? data.OrderBy(sort) : data.OrderByDescending(sort);

Used for filtering data based on search criteria.



var searchTerm = request.Search;
var filteredData = string.IsNullOrEmpty(searchTerm)
    ? query
    : query.Where(x => x.Name.Contains(searchTerm));

Specifies which column/field should be used for sorting the data.



var sortField = request.Sort ?? "id";
var query = data.OrderBy(sortField);

Provides a standardized response format for Bootstrap-Table server-side pagination.
Includes total count, total not filtered, and rows of data matching Bootstrap-Table's expected response format.

> [!NOTE]
> The response format follows Bootstrap-Table's server-side pagination specification

> [!TIP]
> Use this class when implementing server-side pagination with Bootstrap-Table

Example response body:
```json
{
  "total": 50,
  "totalNotFiltered": 100,
  "rows": [
    {
      "id": 1,
      "name": "John Doe",
      "email": "john@example.com"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "name": "Jane Smith",
      "email": "jane@example.com"
    }
  ]
}
```



var response = new PaginationResponse<UserModel>
{
    Total = totalFilteredRecords,
    TotalNotFiltered = totalRecords,
    Rows = users.Skip(offset).Take(limit).ToList()
};
return response;

